reviewText: I thought this was a great idea and I really wanted it so I could show it off.  I received the watch, new, with all necessary items included.  The schedule was easy to load.  However, for some strange reason, it did not play the school's fight song.  I think it had the National Anthem, instead.  I contacted the company and was given an upload to fix this.  Well, the season ended and I was able to show off my watch that cost me a hundred bucks.  Now, I can just go on the website and download the basketball schedule, right?  Except, it costs Money to do that.  And, at the time (a few years ago) I bought this, they did not have the UF basketball schedule available.  Then I learned the saddest part of all when I went to upload the following season's football schedule.  To update the schedule every year for football, it costs extra money.I was very unhappy with that fact.  It was not mentioned anywhere when I first purchased this years ago.  The battery crapped out after a year and a half and I decided it wasn't worth paying the extra money each year for a battery and for the new upload.Also, the USB adapter that connects to the watch isn't very well made.  The piece that grips it to the watch broke after the second upload.  I was able to hold it in place and successfully use it, but just thought I'd let you know to be very careful when using it.Two more things; 1.  It defaults all games to 12 O'clock and will not update when the times change throughout the year.  How lousy is that?  You pay for one upload, you get only one upload.  2.  It does give you the schedule for other SEC teams.  That was pretty cool.

reviewText: This is a great tie and it arrived earlier than promised.  Unlike the competitor's ties, this one depicts a three leaf clover rather than a four leaf clover.  That is significant, because Saint Patrick used a three leaf clover to explain the doctrine of the Trinity to the pagans.  The four leaf clover, in contrast, symbolizes dumb luck.  The Holy Spirit converted an entire nation through Saint Patrick, so this three leaf clover tie is a fitting way of remembering God's grace.
title: Saint Patrick's Day Clover Necktie
description: Don't get caught with out any green on this Saint Patrick's day. This Saint Patrick's Day necktie will  show your St. Patrick's Day spirit with style!

reviewText: Good coverage on the face (as one reviewer stated, I too bought some Oakley half jacket 2.0 and they were too small on my face).  $50 for plastic sunglasses is just ridiculous, I won these and got them free at a promotion event.  Other than the style and ability to change lenses, I do not see the value.  Compared to the Oakley's, these do feel a little more substantial, like safety glasses.  My BIG problem with these are the lenses.  They scratch easily and are a PITA to clean!!!!  They like to get this milky/foggy coating that won't come off the glasses.  Water won't work, the cloth they give you won't work, you need to get soap and water and go at them to really get the lenses clean. I work outdoors and I noticed that after a few weeks the plastic on the earpieces is starting to "shred" and hang off in little wisps, same with the nose pieces.  I use these as my back-up glasses and was able to find replacement lenses for $18 online.  I am going to keep them as my back up at work.  Wiley X is or was one of the contract providers for the military, so I look at that as a little suspect. That doesn't tell me they are "tough", just that Wiley was probably the lowest bid on the contract!
summary: Good coverage, fairly durable, some issues

reviewText: I was disappointed with my order, because the wrong shoe size was sent to me, even again when the replacement order was sent.  I had followed up with an email to the customer service area regarding my reorder size, but it was obvious that they did not read the email I had sent to them.  I just wish they would have read the email and followed up with me before shipping the replacement order.  Perhaps then, the correct size would have been sent out with the second order.  I had questioned the size (10) that was shipped (I am a 7) and had wanted to know if the size was imbedded in the description, or if the 10 was just an item number.  It wasn't clear to me.  Since I received no response from them, the "contact us" service should be rated as Zero!  Also, rather than sending the shoes back a second time, I ended up giving them away to someone that will hopefully be able to use them.  On a positive note, the original order's replacement process itself was fairly easy to follow and the automated replacement service was prompt.  Normally, I have great success with Amazon, but not in this case.  I am being generous by rating this 3 stars.  I am doing so, because I had ordered a different style at the same time and they arrived as ordered.

reviewText: First of all, this organizer contains many tiny pockets, not one of which is big enough for a smartphone. I can barely squeeze my iPod Touch (without the case) into the largest, and it's not something I'd want to fiddle with every time I took it out. Second, it doesn't sit open in your purse the way it does in the picture. There's no reinforcement on the short sides; they're just fabric. The two top edges come together, so that if you drop something into your purse, it's likely to slide down the outside of the organizer and end up underneath it, where you will swear you've lost it and panic then spend 20 minutes mentally retracing your steps to remember where you could have left your keys before you think to dump everything out and find you had them all along. Yes, there's a key clip, but who uses that? It takes far less time to dig something out of an unorganized purse than it does to actually use this organizer.On the plus side, if you disagree with the above, the construction does appear to be sturdy and spills do indeed wipe clean.

reviewText: I've had my Casio G-shock G7900MS-1B black watch with blue trim for about a week now, and I'm absolutely delighted with it.  It keeps great time, it's comfortable on my wrist, the rich blue trim against the black surfaces is appealing yet masculine, and there are so many fun features on the thing that it's more like a wrist toy than simply a wristwatch.One of the coolest and most useful features is called "auto-electro-luminescence" or "Auto-E.L." for short.  With this feature, you can set the watch so that the back-lighting lights up whenever you raise your wrist up toward your eye to check the time.  The screen stays lit up for 5 seconds.  This feature is extremely useful if, say, you've got one hand on your telephone and want to check the time of the phone call, without putting the phone down to push the little back-light "on" button with your other hand.  You turn the auto-EL on or off with the push of one button.  Furthermore, the auto-EL turns off automatically after six hours, to conserve battery life.  This is really useful if, say, you turn the auto-EL on at bedtime, because it will automatically turn off approximately when day breaks the next morning.  As you can see from reading my review, I'm delighted with this feature.There are lots of other cool features as well: you can set the watch to beep each hour, or not.  With the "timer" function, you can count off a period of time (say, 15 minutes of break time from a conference), and the watch will beep when the 15 minutes have elapsed.  You can also set the timer function to automatically repeat over and over again - say, when you want your child to begin her homework after a 10 minute break, and she begs for another 10 minutes and you give in, over and over again.The phases of the moon function is pure, meaningless folly, but fun.  Yes, I have found that it accurately displays the correct phase of the moon, but who really needs this information??? If you're in a profession that really needs this information, say -- an astronaut on a flight to the moon --- I suspect that you're going to have other, more sophisticated sources of determining the phase of the moon and it won't be left up to you and your Casio.  But, it's fun nonetheless.  And the tides?  who really cares?  What are you going to do - walk into a room and announce, "it's 8:30 am, and by the way, it's Neap Tide in the Chesapeake Bay ..."  But again, harmless fun.The watch has an easy toggle between 12/24 hour time display, a feature I find useful as an emergency services worker.  Date and day of the week are also prominently displayed in the main display.  The face of the watch is quite legible -- I find many watch faces annoying these days because all the secondary features tend to get in the way of simply telling the time, but this Casio model avoids that annoying pitfall.The buttons are easy to use and watch appears very well-made.  And it's inexpensive enough so I don't have to fret over getting it scratched, worn, or roughed-up.  I've worn it in business settings and while exercising with equal comfort and confidence.  I'm not a computer expert, but with the help of the manual and about 30 minutes of studying it in a quiet place away from children and other distractions, I was able to master all of its many features (stopwatches, timer, alarms, auto-EL, "world time", etc.).I have to sit through a lot of meetings, conferences, etc., and they are somtimes overlong and boring and I have a bit of ADHD, so my Casio is a lovely little, innocuous distraction during these eternal meetings. My children think the watch is cool, too.If there is any negative at all, it is simply that the watch is rather large.  Even though it's very light-weight, you will still notice it at times on your wrist due to the size, and it will catch on things when, for example, reaching into the back of a crowded regrigerator to get something at the back.I would heartily recommend this fun, attractive, quality, multi-function watch to anyone and everyone.
summary: A really cool, useful, attractive, huge wristwatch.

reviewText: I was looking for a digital watch to use for track, and I decided to pick this up at the reasonable price of roughly $33. As any Timex Ironman you get the time, day of the week, day of the month, the month, a chronograph (timer), and 3 alarms. Also like any Timex Ironman it is very reliable, well working, and lightweight, which you probably already knew. But out of them all you should definitely opt for this specific model, mainly for its exclusivity among other digital watches you may say being worn during any kind of sport. It is roughly 43 mm going from left to right, which is a good size for a dress watch and quite large for a sports digital watch such as this. The orange case is also unique and a very bright, colorful, and nice touch. FYI if you are worrying about the extra size causing the watch to weigh more, don't bother, it is still practically inconceivable on your wrist as of weight. Overall this is a strong and tough watch to wear during whatever sport you do, and has a pleasant and unique touch that will stand it out from the crowd. 10/10.

reviewText: I was looking for a true deep sea watch (for scuba diving) without the hefty price and the Wenger Aquagraph hit the mark. Easy to read, great luminescence, clean design, and a rugged case. The bezel moves easily and has large numbers for quick reference.The rubber strap is substantial and good for everyday use but if you plan on wearing it over a wet ot dry dive suit, I would recommend purchasing the Wenger Deep Diver Kit (also through Amazon)which includes a strap extension which you will need to use to wear the watch over the bulk of a suit. The kit also includes replacement straps, and a screwdriver (for the strap pins) all in a compact case.My only suggestion to Wenger to make this watch perfect would to make the primary watch band longer so that you don't need the strap extension because it is bulky.

reviewText: This is my second vibralite watch.  I used to have a Tissot years ago that had a vibrating alarm. I loved it but lost it somewhere that I couldn't return to (don't ask).  Finally, I found another vibrating watch.  I get up an hour before my wife which makes this watch something I can't live without.  I also set it during the day on vibrate for important calls and activities.  I am a teacher and it's nice to have a silent way of reminding me (alarms going off in class or meetings is a no no.
title: Vibralite 3 Vibration Watch - Stainless Steel
description: The VibraLITE vibrating watch is a great silent reminder. It features an auto restart countdown mode that vibrates at a specified time interval (e.g., every two hours). Once the watch vibrates (for approximately 20 seconds), it automatically resets and counts down again. Each day, you restart the preset countdown mode for continuous interval reminders. Works great when a silent alert is desired at fixed intervals. You may choose sound and/or vibration. Stainless Steel band model is great for a more sophisticated look. Standard size watch face.

reviewText: The good:Good, solid watch.  Keeps time well.  Love the tritium vials; really quite useful in the middle of the night when I'd otherwise be unable to see the watch face.  It's also durable; I'm surprised the band and crystal haven't broken a dozen times over by now.The bad:Amazon ain't an authorized seller of Luminox products (shame, really, for the price).  I didn't buy mine here because buying from an unauthorized source would void the warranty and severely increase my chances of inadvertently getting a fake.  That knocked off a star.  Instead, I purchased from a dealer that came very, very well recommended by friends of mine (and only spent about $25+shipping more).

description: The Luminox Steel Colormark Watch is designed with a constant glow that lasts for up to 25 years. The Luminox Steel Colormark Watch has a 44mm diameter dial that is large enough to use all of the included tools, but doesn't get in the way. And you are not limited to land with this watch! It has a water resistance of 200 meters or 600 feet. The 395 battery has a life of 60 months. The movement technology is quartz Ronda 515 HH6. The Luminox Steel Colormark Watch case is PC carbon reinforced, as is the bezel, with a unidirectional turning bezel at 12h colored LLT protected by hardened mineral glass window. These watches have an antireflective coating. A case back has to be just as strong as the rest of the watch, and the Luminox Steel Colormark Watch does not disappoint. reviewText: I used to work as a kids ski instructor and this is what we'd use for the beginner kids at the ski resort.  Definitely a lifesaver because it would help kids ski their first day on the slopes.  They do come off every now & then, but not as often at the red "Lucky Bums Tip Clip" with the velcro.  You will have to screw the "Easy Wedge" onto the skis tight, which does mark up the tips of the skis, but it's well worth it.  Also you'll need to unscrew one side before getting in the lift line so the kids can widen their skis apart enough to shuffle up to the chair.  You have to then reattach that side before heading downhill again.  I find most kids are content & patient with this process.  Sometimes kids won't wait at the top of the hill & take off!  If they do, you just catch up to where they wiped out, or you discover they don't need them anymore.
title: Lucky Bums Easy Wedge Ski Training Aid
description: Finally an alternative is here with the Lucky Bums Easy Wedge!  Made of more durable material than other products on the market, the Easy Wedge is the quintessential confidence booster making kids more comfortable on their skis by helping them form a wedge to facilitate turns, control speed, and on that last run of the day when they are feeling a bit tired.  Keep the Easy Wedge in your pocket and use whenever your kids try new or more aggressive terrain.

reviewText: I have had the watch for only 4 days or so and really like it.  However I am a little disappointed in the battery life, there is no way it's anywhere near 5 days. reviewText: Well I have to admit that this is the most expensive watch that I've ever owned.  I think my highest priced one was less than a hundred bucks.  Moving up to the $650 range was a big jump for me.  The photo on this webpage doesn't do the watch justice, it's like looking at a fuzzy outline of a beautiful woman compared to seeing her in person!  This watch is simply breathtaking.I love that it has a chronograph but it's not too busy like most and you can easily see what time it is at a quick glance.  For some reason I thought this watch had a screw down crown but it doesn't.  And the bezel doesn't rotate.  The user manual said you can use it for swimming and snorkling but not scuba diving, you need 200 m water resistance for that.  It also says that you shouldn't use it in a hot tub or it can leak from the heat, interesting.  I also thought the tritium would glow a bit brighter than it does, it's rather dim but it is readable in any light if you look close.I had to bring it to the shop to get one link removed and they charged me ten bucks, probably because they saw an expensive watch and figured I could afford it, they were right!  Getting the watch serviced may be tricky depending on where you live.  Here in Colorado there is only one shop that is qualified to work on it.  You can see the shops at the traser.com website.  I really love the gun metal grey band, it's really solid and has a good feel to it.  It looks like it would be extremely scratch resistant and it you did happen to scratch it I bet it wouldn't show very much because of the textured finish which is like a very fine sand blasted finish.By the way, it's not listed on this site but the face is 40mm which is a really nice 'normal' watch size.  The face may be a little thick but I don't think its out of balance with the watch.  Overall I would highly recommend this watch, at least now that I've owned it for half a day.  Hopefully in a few weeks or months my review won't change!~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~Update:  I weighed my watch today and it was 112.2 grams with one link missing.  By the way, I tried to find another watch that had tritium tubes, a titanium band, and a sapphire crystal and I can't find one anywhere.  Apparently this watch has no competition if you want those three things!~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~Another update:  Well I wore the watch to bed last night and woke up in the middle of the night to see how bright it was and lo and behold it was really really bright!  I guess it just takes some time for your eyes to get used to the darkness and this thing really lights up!

title: Pyle Sports Snorkeling Master Watch
description: With this snorkeling watch from Pyle Sports, you’ll always be ready to handle the elements. The special dive-ready design provides water resistance up to 10 atmospheres — that’s 330 feet. The PSNKW30 reports your depth up to a resolution of 0.1 ft and is equipped with a dive alarm that activates when emerging faster than 6m per minute. The watch is also equipped with a thermometer to measure the temperature of the water to 1 degree Celsius or Fahrenheit. Best of all, all this data is stored in the dive log, which holds up to 100 records, including your time and date, dive duration, maximum dive depth, min. water temperature, and dive site indication. Electro-luminescent backlight means you’ll always know the time, day or night. Color: black.

reviewText: I like to wait awhile before I review items to see if they live up to my expectations.  I bought a pair of these pants about a year ago and they do...so much so that I bought another pair about a month ago.My work is outside and requires a lot of kneeling on concrete, asphalt, or rocky ground while repairing equipment.  These are the best pants I have ever owned in more than 25 years of this work.Some things I like about these pants:1. A year later and the original pair I bought shows hardly any wear.2. The extra wide/long belt loops don't tear off like thin ones do.3. The knee pads are removeable so I can use one pair for both pairs of pants.4. The knee pad pockets are built-in, so I don't have to mess with straps that are either so loose that they slip down or are so tight thay they chafe the back of my knee and/or cut off the circulation to my leg.5. Each knee pad pocket has a pocket inside on the bottom so the knee pad will not fall out.6. I can put items in the utility pockets and wear the pockets outside my seatbelt when I'm driving so I can easily reach in to get something.7. The fabric is strong and durable (see #1), yet they are breathable enough to not get overheated in hot summer weather.8. There are more than enough pockets for everything I usually carry.Some things I don't like about these pants:A year later and I still really can't think of anything.  Yes, they are a bit pricey, but they are worth every penny.  They last long enough to more than make up for the extra expense.  I will be getting more in the future so I can throw away my "swiss cheese" pants.I have had many people see these pants and ask me where I got them.  I tell them to go to Amazon.com and search for Blaklader (which I have to spell for them).  OK, maybe an easier name would be nice!8/24/13One minor negative and one suggestion for improvement.  The kneepads location is a little low for me, so I have to hike up my pants before I kneel down or else my knees will hit the ground above the pads.  The suggestion is that they make these with shin pads as well!  Ouch!The first pair of pants I bought a few years ago finally developed a hole in one knee and the zipper pull broke off.  They are still very usable, though, and I will.

reviewText: I bought two pairs last summer. I figured that I would use them for the summer and still get use out of them for winter. I bought LL.Bean and the shoe was great quality but they no long stocked it. I thought I would try these. Well, The verdict is in and they did an excellent job.The reason I bought these in the first place was they are easy to slip-on and off and they are good snow shoes for fast trips in winter. I live in Chicago and our winters can get wet. Driving the kids in the morning was simple. I didn't have to tie anything and didn't need hands to get them off. The traction on the bottom of the shoe has groves so slipping and sliding is minimum.They are great gardening shoes in the summer. My daughter was wearing them brief yesterday to take are our annual flowers outside. She stepped in mud. All I had to do was wash them off with the hose and hang them out to dry.I did take one pair with me camping two weeks ago. They are great with the morning dew, we got poured on once and my feet were dry. I didn't need the other shoes I packed.The only problem I have is wearing them in sport activities like basketball, a hike..(no support for the ankle)or running. The shoe is not meant for that but I thought I'd mention it. I'm an 8 1/2  so I had to go up a half a size. I wear socks in the winter and my feet expand in the summer.

reviewText: This watch comes with a chain, which is something not depicted in the photos or mentioned in the description.  It is the same chain shown with the Charles-Hubert Paris Mechanical Pocket Watch, and silver in color.The watch itself is beautiful and has some serious weight to it.  It arrived in a black cardboard box within a box, so the packaging has a nice presentation if you are buying this as a gift. The watch was in a black cloth cinched bag inside the inner box. It also comes with rudimentary instructions and a lens cleaning cloth.  The watch itself displays upright very nicely on a desk with its swiveling leg stand.One reviewer said one of the "pins" on the leg stand came out of their watch.  I examined mine and the "pins" actually appear to be tiny phillips head screws.  I can't imagine how they would work themselves out of the watch except through frequent manipulation of the stand or a poor borehole for the screw.  The screws on mine appear to be very secure.The second hand on my watch was at the 30 second mark when it arrived and as soon as I began winding the watch, it began moving.  There is no way to stop the second hand with the stem once it gets moving if you want to set the time precisely to UTC.  So before you begin winding it, if you want to match it to UTC, don't starting winding it until the UTC seconds count is where your second hand is.The front glass cover is large enough to see the entire face of the clock.  The only reason you would ever need to open it to read the time is if you put a photo in the cover.  The glass cover does screw off for ease of placing a photo in it, and the bezel is studded so you can grip it easily enough to unscrew it.The back of the watch presents a very sensual, buttery look with the brass casing and inner works visible through the rear glass.  All of the crystals are glass on this piece, not plastic.Make sure you read the instructions before winding the watch or fiddling with the stem to open and close the cover.  It takes all of one minute to fully understand the instructions, but they are important to read and understand.This watch is definitely worth the price.  (Edited to add: This watch was $90.00 when I bought it.)

reviewText: I travel a lot and am used to wearing heels 24x7. However, I found NuFoot footwear and now carry them with me for running thru the airport. It's like going barefoot but your feet stay clean.-They fold up (I fold them inside out so they don't get my bag dirty) and I can tuck them away until my next airport run.-When I get home, I throw them in the wash and they're good to go for my next trip.-I have bought them in different colors, to coordinate with my outfits, which is a bonus.-The rubberized tread on the bottom keeps me from slipping on slippery floors, perfect traction.-I'm tall with bigger feet than normal so was concerned the largest size wouldn't fit. However, the L fits fine on my size 10 feet. I don't think they'd fit an 11, however. (probably too short)Issues to consider - they have no support or much padding. This works fine for me but it also means that you can feel the ridges on an escalator, for example.These footies/slippers get a lot of comments. I've been asked repeatedly if they are socks or slippers by flight attendants, gate agents, travelers and even the shoe shine guy in the San Antonio airport.Love them - they're a great value for the price.

reviewText: I've used Diadora road bike shoes for years. I knew very well that 42 was my size, and even then I still purchased from brick and mortar bicycle shops to verify fit. I will never purchase cycling shoes online ever again. Also, they aren't "yellow"... it's neon green. Thought they would match my black and yellow Masi, but they don't.

reviewText: I absolutely love this bag!!  My sister recommend Keen's bags to me (she's had hers for seven years sans problem), and I fully understand why she's so enthusiastic about this brand.The bag is little smaller than I wanted, but a 1L Nalgene bottle fits with room for my wallet, a book, or even a couple DVDs (I frequent my local library).  I've considered buying a slightly smaller water bottle for a bit more space though.  The pockets and places to store little items are plentiful with two inside zippers and one small outside zipper.  The back snap pocket is perfect for frequently used items such as a phone.I'm thoroughly impressed by the water resistance of the outside; a heavy downpour caught me and the outside of my bag was drenched, but its contents was dry.  Finally, I'm surprised by how much I like the magnetic closure.  I worried it wouldn't be strong enough to keep the flap closed, but if the flap catches, the magnet draws it closed again.There's only one downside: The strap, while it doesn't loosen, rubs on my neck.  There isn't any padding along the entire strap which is fine when I wear a t-shirt or jacket, but it's a bit uncomfortable with a tanktop.Overall though, an outstanding bag!!  I highly recommend :)

reviewText: I won this wallet in a trivia contest back in 2007 at a BMW enthusiast meetup where BMW was on hand to launch the new BMW performance line of parts. The leather felt exactly like the leather in my E36 M3, and smelled like one too.  The only complaint I have is that when you put any more than $300 in 20's in the wallet, it starts to not close all the way.  This wallet was very durable, even going through the washer a few times, as well as falling in the pool/ or getting thrown in the ocean, and even after all those, no discoloration, or fade to the wallet, and the emblem never chipped or lost any of the blue/white pattern.I highly recommend this wallet to anyone who likes BMW

reviewText: The only reason I'm not wearing this watch right now is because I have on typing gloves.  I wear this all the time.  It's very comfortable and stylish.  Even my mom, who doesn't like large watches, thought this was nifty.And it is a relatively large watch.  The center section is over an inch wide, while the rest of the band is probably about half an inch (my best guesstimates).  For all that, though, it's not masculine.  It's not a refined watch, but it's both functional and fashionable.  I've knocked mine around plenty in the last year or so, and it's still ticking.  It's a little beat up now (I wasn't joking about knocking it around), but I received many compliments when I first bought it.  I don't much use the center section but it's pretty easy to read.My only complaint is that when one side of the face came loose from its "leather" moorings, it was really difficult to not only get back in but to also keep it back in.  It's probably something you can have a jeweler or a watch-person or a really handy individual do for you, but, for me, it kept happening at really awkward times.  Eventually my really handy uncle fixed the situation and I haven't had trouble with it since.  Perhaps the thing to do is have it checked out immediately and avoid the problem?  With that issue fixed, however, I haven't had any trouble with this watch.  I'll be very sad if/when it dies on me.

reviewText: Overall I'm happy with my Pebble watch. The battery life is awesome and it's always easy to read. It's starting to get some really great apps now too. Here are some of the problems I've had with it.1.) Connecting to your cell phone can take a really long time. It usually takes me three tries to get it to connect, it always starts working on the 3rd attempt. I wonder why.2.) The glass is very easily scratched! You definitely need a screen protector. I have two giant gouges and the funny thing is, I have no idea how or why. They just appeared. I'm sure I did something, but I don't remember it going through any trauma.3.) The charger isn't super great. The magnet that keeps it together is pretty week and you can't plug it into a wall to charge. You can only plug it in to a computer via USB to charge. It would be much more convenient if I could plug it in.4.) There aren't many good options for covers and cases. Maybe I'm just picky, I just wish there was a bigger variety. Most of them are stickers. If there were more snap on/snap offs to match different outfits and I'd be much happier.Overall, it's a good product. I'd somewhat recommend, just take note of some of it's downfalls.

reviewText: I took this watch to Montana fly fishing. It gives you altitude and barometric pressure, as well as a compass. Oh, and time too. The baro pressure was nice because it predicted some weather changes for us. Great watch, and I also like the backlight on demand function so you can read it in total darkness when you need to. It has an alarm too, but either from artillery ear (from the service) or surfer's ear from living on the left coast, or just living through the 1960s, I can't hear it well enough that it would even alert me to anything.
title: Suunto Core Black Military
description: Building on the success of the venerable Suunto Vector, the Suunto Core keeps you informed of conditions while you hike, bike, or camp, making it a terrific companion for outdoor enthusiasts of all stripes. What can the Suunto Core do for you? For starters, it can sense an approaching squall even when the sky looks clear. This intelligent Storm Alarm--one of several intelligent features designed to keep you safe and secure--is activated by a rapid drop in air pressure over a three-hour period. Once the Core senses the change, the Storm Alarm sounds and flashes, letting you know that something unpleasant is fast approaching. The built-in altimeter, meanwhile, displays your current elevation, shows how much you've climbed or descended, and records your entire session for later analysis. Accurate to within 30,000 feet, the altimeter is an extremely valuable tool for mountaineering, backcountry skiing, and wilderness travel. Add in such features as a barometer, a digital thermometer, a weather trend indicator, and a digital compass and you have a terrific wrist-top computer for almost all your outdoor needs. Additional features include several traditional watch functions, including dual times, a date display, and an alarm; predicted times for sunrise and sunset to help you maximize your daylight hours; an automatic Alti/Baro mode that senses movement or lack thereof and switches between the altimeter and barometer accordingly; a depth meter that provides accurate water depth readings to 30 feet; and the ability to function in English, German, French, and Spanish. The Suunto Core carries a two-year warranty.

reviewText: With 4,000 miles of hiking experience under my Vibrams, this is the best boot I have ever worn. But a word of caution - evaluating footwear is a VERY personal thing. The optimal boot for anyone IS THE ONE THAT FITS BEST! For me the Garmont Flash III GTX was the ticket. Any boot should be tried on inside the store first and tested on both flat surfaces and inclines wearing the socks you will be using on the trail (knowledgeable sales assistants can educate you on the critical aspects of proper fit). I was able to purchase these online without a test drive because they are my second pair. They probably won't have the durability of a pure leather boot but the trade-off in comfort and light weight was well worth it. And, even on my blister-prone feet, they fit like a glove with almost no break-in mileage necessary.

reviewText: I was really drawn to the design of this watch and I wanted it to work.  Notwithstanding the other reviews, I realized that I could only get an accurate temperature reading with the watch off my wrist.  No big deal...all the other watches that measure temperature are like that too.  I liked the elastic type strap furnished with this particular model.  It looked good, was comfortable and worked well with a metal clasp for both direct wrist use and over outer clothing.About 10 days into wearing it the watch went blank?  No hard use just everyday normal wear.  The rear battery compartment was a twist off and was easy to get into but was not loose?  The battery measured full juice...OK!?  I reinserted the battery and tightened the cap and voila' the display came back on and I reset all functions.  The watch appeared to be functioning normally and I wore it for a few more days but the barometer would not budge from its 10.-- inHG reading?I decided not to fool with it anymore and returned the watch to Amazon for a refund.  I was disappointed but decided to pay a little more for a new Casio PAW2000-1.  We'll see how that goes?
summary: I really wanted it to work!

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

reviewText: I love this watch!!!  The build quality and precision you come to expect in a Swiss watch is all here.  The bezel is all stainless and the glass face is clear and big (not too big though, like those "other" outdoor watches).  It's a heavy watch and it's ready to do battle in the outdoors.  The band is exceptionally nice with matching red stitching, a stainless buckle, and sturdy, bendy water proof silicon construction.  The compass portion of the watch is dead on when properly calibrated (easy to do).  The instructions are easy to follow and guide you through all the settings for the watch.  As nice as this watch is, two things to keep in mind for the future would be: battery replacement and band replacement.  The battery is not user serviceable and will need to be replaced by a shop that has the special tool to remove the back (typical with all fine watches).  The band itself, if ever needing replacement, looks expensive and may be difficult to obtain (probably only through Wenger). But overall, if you are looking at this watch because you want a digital compass watch (the reason I bought it)  with a little more sophistication, metal construction and Swiss reliability, than this is the only watch of it's kind out there for the price.  A great value!

reviewText: I almost hate to give such a low rating, but the watch and the company are just bad. I understand this is a kickstarter startup company, but given the time that has passed and the fact you can buy the watch ate best buy the lack of professionalism is inexcusable.The hardware itself is probably fine, but it is hard to tell since all the support software is buggy and unstable. The only redeeming software is made by third parties and is constantly being broke by buggy patches from pebble. After the last firmware my watch will no longer connect to my phone and I am not sure I even want to bother figuring out why.While I love that so many good apps are produced by third party developers, I fell most are getting fed up dealing with bugs produced by pebble in updates. Now most of the stable apps are pay apps which I wouldn't mine except to have a watch that does much more then tell the time expect to drop another $50 plus on pay apps.In short, I do not recommend this product and barring a major change in the company itself I would be surprised if it still exists in five years.

reviewText: This was purchased as a tech toy. Smart watches are still in their infancy. Even so, this unit is well thought out, and even for its simple design, it does a fairly good job.The watch comes with a set of 'faces' (digital, not physical) which are different watch faces to tell time. You can download more via the companion application you have to install on your smart phone. Yes, you have to pair it with a phone to use it. The companion application offloads things like information retrieval (weather, GPS, etc) from the watch, reducing the electronic complexity in the watch itself.There are other applications you can download into the watch beyond the basic watch faces. There are 8 storage spaces in the watch to run them. Some may come in 2 parts, and this take two spaces. So it is no memory behemoth. You are not going to upload your MP3 collection into it. It doesn't even have speakers to play them anyway. Also of note: the watch does not run two programs at once. You run the one you want, switch to another and the first is shutdown.It does have a 'buzzer' motor built in. It can be used to tick off the hour, or used as an alarm. Very quiet and effective, unless you suffer from some nerve damage that leaves your arm numb to sensations like that.One application I use beyond the information tools, is a sleep monitor. It samples the watch's built in accelerometer while it is running, to get an idea if you are sound asleep, lightly asleep, or seemingly wake (tossing and turning). The companion app can then give you a chart in the morning of how you did. It also has a smart alarm function that will wake you up, theoretically at the best point within a wake up time range you set. This isn't a serious health application. But it is a good toy that gives you insight into you sleep patterns.Battery life is fair. It certainly beats a typical phone's battery. I charge my PEBBLE every four or five days, when it is down around 30 or 40 %.Construction is solid. You are NOT ever going to open this thing up to change the batter or explore. People who have done that end up with a badly 'damaged' watch that requires nasty glue jobs to get it back into workable shape. So, in essence this is a throw away toy. If it dies, you are not going to get it repaired (when outside of its warranty). But at its price, compared to other smart watches, it hurts a bit less to let it go.If the price is too steep to you, then yes, it is too steep. This is not a watch you will keep for years and years. There are far better watches you can buy, to tell time with. This is an early stage smart watch in a world where people think they must trade their cellular phone out for a new one every 2 years or so. It would be so nice if they made a smart watch with an expected 10 year life cycle, with replaceable parts. This isn't that.The requirement to tie it to your iOS or Android smart phone, reduces its value a bit. But then, if it could gather information all on its own, it would cost a heck of a lot more. So it is a good entry point to explore the ideas of what a smarter watch can be.

reviewText: The case looks and feels cheaply made.  The four buttons don't always make contact when I press them.  The display resolution is OK, but just that.  It is certainly not up to the standards of a Kindle "paper display" and I was expecting lots better.  The band is unnecessarily thick.  This might have been done in the interest of stylishness and given the way the rest of the watch looks, why bother?  Granted, you can replace the band but...Physical characteristics aside, When I place my (pre) order many months ago there weren't any.  Today there are barely more than that.  You should check to make sure what you want is available and is usable.  For example, the is an app that controls music on your mobile device except there is no way to change the volume.  There are plenty of alternate clock faces and many are round with their sides cut off by the Pebble rectangular display.Some stuff does work. For example, text messages and caller ID displays just fine.  A few other things work, albeit with limited functionality as well.  The question is, do you want to have that stuff if it comes on a watch that looks and feels like a child's toy?UPDATE:  I must acknowledge Pebble Customer Service.  After a week they responded to my question about their return policy by sending me an RMA.  I will update the review again if I ever get my refund.

title: Pyle Sports Snorkeling Master Watch
description: With this snorkeling watch from Pyle Sports, you’ll always be ready to handle the elements. The special dive-ready design provides water resistance up to 10 atmospheres — that’s 330 feet. The PSNKW30 reports your depth up to a resolution of 0.1 ft and is equipped with a dive alarm that activates when emerging faster than 6m per minute. The watch is also equipped with a thermometer to measure the temperature of the water to 1 degree Celsius or Fahrenheit. Best of all, all this data is stored in the dive log, which holds up to 100 records, including your time and date, dive duration, maximum dive depth, min. water temperature, and dive site indication. Electro-luminescent backlight means you’ll always know the time, day or night. Color: black.

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

title: Casio PRW 3000 Watch
description: The Casio PRW 3000 Watch won't cook your dinner, carry your gear, or give you a foot rub after a long hike, but it'll do just about everything else you can imagine on your next trek, backpacking trip, sailing mission, or time-traveling adventure. This little aluminum, resin, and mineral glass case packs a mind-boggling array of tech tools, from an altimeter to a barometer to a compass to a thermometer, all run by a solar-powered battery that'll last for up to seven months on a single charge. The altimeter, which measures in precise one-meter increments, has automatic and manual logging functions and can hold up to 30 records of high/low altitudes, cumulative ascent and descent, with a range from -2,300 to over 32,000 feet. That's just the beginning. The PRW 3000 has a barometer as well, which has an automatic pressure-change indicator to alert you to sudden swings, along with a pressure tendency graph and pressure differential graphic to give you a longer-term idea of what the weather's doing. To keep you on course, the compass has a graphic 16-point display for one-glance orientation, a bearing memory to keep you on route, and declination adjustment so your bearing is accurate no matter where in the world you are. We haven't even mentioned the one thing the PRW 3000's designed to do first and foremost--tell the time. It receives six atomic signals a day to ensure you're always on time, has 12- and 24-hour displays and five alarms so you never miss a mealtime, and sunset/sunrise, time zone, and calendar data. There isn't even space to discuss the stopwatch, 100m waterproofing, automatic LED, power-save function, or battery-life indicator, but trust that they're there.

title: Glitter AmberWatch
description: The most effective means of protecting children from predators is giving them tools to prevent abduction. The AmberWatch was designed to complement safety plans made with parents and to aid in an immediate escape. It is a 115-decibel alarm built into a watch that, when activated, can be heard from 100 yards away. An unmistakable distress signal, it draws attention to dangerous situations and helps children respond strongly when they feel threatened. It can also come into use when a child is lost in a store, park or crowd, when they’re threatened by an animal, if they’re hurt, or if they get lost while participating in activities such as camping, skiing or hiking. The watch has a bulky modern style and super-bright LED lights that can be seen night or day. Digital functions include time, date, alarm, stopwatch, day of the week, low battery and backlight. The alarm is activated by pushing both of the red buttons on either side of the face and deactivated using the same 2 buttons in a coded sequence you set yourself. A special break-away back-up system automatically activates the alarm if the watch is forcibly removed. Amber Watch donates $1 to the AmberWatch Foundation for every watch sold. Water resistant. Adjusts to 6 sizes, approx. 5-3/4L" to 7-3/4L". Purple glitter bezel with a purple band.Features and BenefitsEmits 115 decibelsSuper bright LED lightsSpecial break-away back-up systemMultiple functionsFashionable and life-saving

reviewText: I was initially sceptical (for my use) of these knee warmers as they seemed far too thick. reviewText: I live in remote Alaska.  I don't think I need to say anything about wanting to stay warm.These booties keep my feet warm on the cold cabin floor down into the -40 range.  They aren't the most stylish looking things in the world, but who cares when it's -40 out?  I'm not a fashionista anyway!This product is lightweight and I have taken them out camping.  I would not say they are good for using outdoors - the sole of the booty is not set up for that, and as such, they're better for the house.My only complaint is that the fabric on the sole did not last as long as I would have like.  About 5 months of daily use I developed a couple of small holes, but just the fabric.  And easy fix - I used a spreadable silicon on the sole and after it set - it took care of the problem.  An added benefit is now the sole is waterproof and slip-proof.Comfortable and warm booties.  I highly suggest.

reviewText: A disclaimer here. I'm a writer and I have very little patience with poorly written instructions. And if ever there was product--handy, attractive, not too expensive--that deserves decent instructions, it's this one.I have but 28 days to review this product. . . and I may just figure it all out in that time. But it shouldn't be that hard. Instructions need to be arranged first things first.  So, first how to set it to measure heart rate, then information on setting time. And it needs to be step-by-step.Mind you, I love digital watches. I have had at least two dozen in the last two years--one in practically every color of the rainbow and many different manufacturers, including Timex. So I'm not unfamiliar with how to set these guys. But this one has more features so it is naturally a more intricate process. And that takes me back to my original statement: A product this good needs either better instructions or better design.I may end up just using it as a watch and ignore the trainer features altogether.  I mean, I do love the color!

reviewText: I've been using this band for about two weeks now, and I'm done with it.Here is why:1. There is no instruction book that comes with the product, just a bunch of stupid pictures that aren't very helpful. I understand you can google it and find some other instructions, but for $60 Nike really should be giving you instructions on how to use it.2. There are only two buttons. Of the 17 or so runs the website says I've done, at least 5 are completely empty because I couldn't get the screen to go to running mode and it ended up just ending the "run." Can they not put a start and stop button on the thing? Would that be so hard?3. And those 5 empty runs? Yeah, once they're uploading to the website, you can't delete them. Which means all my averages are off, and they are pulling down all the statistics that I actually wanted to look at, hence why I started using the band in the first place.4. Even after calibrating three runs, when I can get the thing to work it is normally short by at least a quarter mile. And, it uploads the uncalibrated runs again to use in the statistics, so my mileage looks a lot shorter than it really is.5. It can't handle sprints or really any change to your stride since it's all based on how many steps you take.Honestly, this thing does not work at all for me. It has taken the fun out of my runs. Maybe other people have had more success with it, but it's worthless to me. I aim to run about 10-15 miles per week and am probably around a 12 minute mile pace and I was using it with a pouch on my laces, not a Nike shoe. I'm very disappointed in the amount of statistics the website COULD be giving me that it just isn't.

reviewText: Yeah, "super" isn't grammatically correct.  But since so many refer to these as "Clark Kent" glasses... well, what other word could I use?  Anyway, they do what they are intended to do.  And, apparently, with some people, they make a marked difference in your appearance.  For example, upon seeing me wearing them for the first time, one friend exclaimed, "I didn't know that you wore contacts!"  When I asked why she said such a thing, she told me that this was the first time she'd seen me in glasses, so I must have been wearing contacts all the other times.  Truth is, over the past 4 years, she has never seen me without glasses.  Admittedly, they were gold tone wire frames.  So, they were about as unobtrusive as glasses can be.  Still, these made such a dramatic difference that she seemed to forget that I'd ever worn glasses at all.  Not much of a stretch from that to see how they'd be a Super(man) disguise.BTW, I've gotten several compliments on my new glasses.  So, this "retro" look is a hit with a number of my friends.  If you order a pair of these, keeping in mind how little you paid and the purpose for which they were created, I expect that you'll be pleased.

reviewText: There is nothing worse than having sweat drip into your eye when exercising. While running this can be a painful annoyance, while on the bike it can be down right dangerous.I live in the UAE where temperatures can reach 50 degrees C and profuse sweat is just a part of the deal. I used to use a bandana but after awhile the bandana would get soaked and the sweat would start dripping into your eyes. The Headsweats Beanie has some elastic toweling which soaks it all up and prevents the sweat from dripping into your eyes.If I had one criticism you do get two lines imprinted into your forehead after your ride/run and you look a little goofy for 30 minutes or so after you've taken it off but i'd rather look goofy any day of the week than go without this simple, elegant and essential piece of kit.Headsweats, well done.

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

reviewText: The concept is great and I was excited by the rev 2.0 software.  Unfortunately, I have to complain about the connectivity issues (like everyone else).  It functions fine as a watch (if a bit on the plain/ugly side), but the connectivity to the phone is not nearly as cool as I would've thought.  90% of the benefit (for me) comes from the fact that it (usually) vibrates when I get texts or notifications from my iPhone, especially when I have my phone on vibrate and don't notice it.  The watch vibrating is pretty good and catches your attention, although I make it a point to keep it charged >50% as much as possible.Having the watch in constant Bluetooth communication with my phone has lowered my iPhone battery life noticeably, but with iOS7 it was already poor so it isn't THAT big a deal for me.Generally, as a "techie" I'm happy I bought it to experiment with "wearable" technology, but I could certainly live without it.

reviewText: Me and my girls (6 and 4) opened the package, discovering the shoes were narrow and a small size. The 4 year old was pleased, but they are really too small for the 6 year old. I could not tell from the pictures, though. Well, ok so far. My girls run away to play dress up, 3 minutes later a huge hullabaloo: Two of the shoes had already lost their bow! After 3 minutes of play - really!??? I calm my girls down and get two additional pairs out of the plastic package and guess what - 5 minutes later another riot breaks lose because a plastic heart on the third pair and another bow on the fourth pair fell off as well! I almost lost my mind, wanting to send back that junk instantly but my little one broke out in tears, wanting to keep the shoes because the colors are so cute... Alright, I fixed everything with stapler and glue and now my girls just line up the shoes for looking at them because they are afraid they might fall apart again when in use. My advice: Do not waste your money on such cheaply made product. It is not worth a dime!

reviewText: Like other reviews said I can't believe someone thought it was agood idea to have the straps attached to the top, on the part that opens, instead of the sides!? I think the most that should prob. be put in it is one big book and binder, if you don't want it to wear out fast. The metal closure in the front is going to give out before the straps ever will, but it's because the straps are attached to the flap instead of the sides, cause all that weight is putting stress on that little metal peice that turns to close. Lots of places to put stuff but I don't recommend it if you want to carry heavy stuff. I've been using it for almost 6 weeks now and I like it but it's too heavy to carry 2 books & 2 binders, I'm starting to carry half in it and the other half in my hands. description: How to set the time:Time: For example: 10:34, the watch LED be lighted up to 10 in upper speedometer, and to 30 in down speedometer plus number 4 which will be lighted up to 4 within the down speedometer.Date: For example: December 1st, the "Date" will be light up, the upper speedometer will be lighted up at "12", the down speedometer will be lighted up at "1".Week: For example: Monday, The "week" will be light up, the upper speedometer will be lighted up at "1".Am/PM showing: When the "PM" lights up, it means the watch time is in afternoon, and when the "PM" lights off, it means the watch time is in Morning. The "AM" could not light up.How to set the brightness:Just press the down setting button several times, when upper speedometer's light is on at "2 6 10 11" and the 1-4 number button is on, then press the down button to set the brightness grade (1-4 grade).How to set the auto timing light up:Press the down setting button several times, when the down speedometer lights up at "ON/OFF" and a number at left side, set a time you like the LED automatically lights up from every 5 to 30 minutes. When the "ON/OFF" lights up, this function is in active status, when you set the "ON/oFF" to flash, this function is closed without operation in a few minutes.Package include:1 x Digital LED Watch1 X Metal box for watch taking

reviewText: I've had my watch for probably 3 or 4 years now. I can't remember because I don't concern myself with it. I wear it everywhere. My parakeet is also inlove with it as a head-scratching post. I bought it to replace a similar watch given to me by my husband when we were expecting our son 9.5 years ago. (The ingiglo feature finally gave out.) The alarm features on the first watch were the best and I wanted that again! I could take a nap anywhere I needed to -- Contrary to some reviews, the alarm is more than enough to wake me up. Later on, it was just plain handy to have a timer, alarm, etc. right on my wrist wherever I went without the bulk of the big watches I'd seen before. Now, my 9.5-year-old son wants a watch with an alarm/timer so that he can remember to come home on time, so I'm getting him this because it's not as bulky, once again, as the men's watches.My only complaint is that it only has 3 alarms (my previous one had five), but that's just an inconvenience, not really a problem. I liked the fact that I had three consistent alarms and two variable, but I've learned to live with three total.

reviewText: I have been interested in this watch since the Kickstarter announcement of development.  My interest was renewed when it was given attention at the Consumer Electronics Show.  While many are now looking forward to the new version, Pebble Steel, I still wanted to get this initial version.  As others have noted, the features developed thus far are limited.  However, these features do address what I want to do with the watch - quick reference to incoming texts, e-mails and notifications; quick identification of incoming calls; and the ability to craft unique watch faces for a different look virtually every day.  There are more apps offering a variety of new capabilities with additional apps in development.  I look forward to exploring those and adapting them for my use.  But even if this watch never added capabilities, I would be very pleased with my purchase.

reviewText: *** Update 5/2/13*** It is a pleasure to report that it has been almost 4.5 years and this product is still working flawlessly. I used it on a 5.5 mile run and it is as good as the day I got it. See comments to this review -- others have made good tips that I agree with. The bottom line -- if you are still using it after this amount of time, you are either ready for an upgrade or at least won't mind having to buy another unit!Original Review:I'd hoped that getting this new running gadget would encourage me to exercise more often. So far so good. I asked for this for Christmas and, well, it has accomplished it's primary function for me... I've been running almost every day since I got it. I was turned off by the gigantic size of some HRMs, and did not need something to keep track of splits as I run on my treadmill at home and the gym.As a heart rate monitor, the functionality is pleasantly simple. It tracks your heart rate for the whole workout. You hit the big button to start, and it goes to work tracking the length of time, the average heartbeat, and the peak. While you are running, it displays your current heartbeat. That's it -- but sometimes it's better to keep it simple.I should point out that, as a watch, the watch piece tells the time and date only. If you want/need splits and a stopwatch, you should look elsewhere.Here's some other thoughts: I was worried that the strap would break but realized after a couple workouts that I was probably wearing it a little too tight. Since adjusting, it is much more comfortable, has not fallen off, and, as a guy, you *almost* forget that you have it on. My wife cracked up when I took my shirt off after a recent workout. She said that, from the back, it looked like I was wearing a bra (or Manzierre, or Bro, if you prefer).I had no original intention of wearing it while NOT working out, but I've found it addictive, and have enjoyed observing how drinking a cup of coffee while sitting at my desk does raise my heart rate about 10-15 beats per minute on average. Also, as I've started to get in a little better shape over the last 3 weeks, I see that I have to run either farther or faster to get my heart rate up to certain thresholds. And, now my heart rate does not go up as high from merely climing the stairs at home. I believe that these insights, among others, are very encouraging for someone who is just getting back in shape. The encouragement aspect combined with the simplicity makes this a great starter heart rate monitor for anyone considering.

reviewText: I love my new Pebble watch!I've owned a lot of the really geeky, no name watches in the past, including the Fossil Abacus watch that ran Palm OS way back in the day and even one of those "MP4" watches they sell on ebay and this definitely my favorite watch I have owned.Its so easy to get set up and start receiving notifications on your wrist! I love all the apps and watch faces that are out their and how easy it is to install them right from your phone. Im really only giving the watch 4 stars due its limit of only 8 watch faces or apps that can be installed at one time. This limit is arbitrary considering how small the file size of the watch faces are compared to some of the larger apps.My only other gripe is that Amazon sent me what is clearly a refurbished watch masquerading as new. The one I got has glue oozing from the side and what are clearly dents in the plastic from an apparent screw driver being jammed into the plastic housing to replace the screen. But Amazons return/exchange policy is easy and convenient so I'm not to worried for now.This watch is definitely a go!

reviewText: Now then, this is a fine digital watch, but there seems to be much confusion as to what the "Water Resist" term means on the face. Simply put, "How wet can I safely get my Casio F-91W?" Now then ISO standard 2281 define what makes a water resist watch.[...]From this text I will quote section 6.2.1"6.2.1 Resistance to air overpressureSubject the watch to an air overpressure of 2 bar[2] and measure the flow rate of air entering the case."Hence we can conclude that any watch bearing the marking "Water Resist", can at minimum survive at a pressure of 2bar, which in water is about 10m. Further reading in section 7.2 implies that could be closer to 20m in water, as air is more permeable.  So Casio owners feel safe, you can dive to the bottom of your local pool and the F-91w should remain intact.
summary: Great Wach: Lets settle the "Water Resist" once and for all

reviewText: An excellent timepiece! I bought this watch to wear with my suit, and couldn't be happier with it. It does come with a silver chain, which is not advertised. This is no cheap Walmart special. There is no plastic on this watch! The entire watch is very "tight" and is thicker and heavier then the pictures depict! It comes with clear instructions and warnings on what to avoid. And the two-tone is a nice touch, it's not a solid color like so many other watches are, thus it does stand out... in a good way! I get nothing but compliments whenever someone sees it.I bought this because 98% of the reviews just raved about this! And they were all spot on! A few of the negative reviews stated that the pins for the stand fell out, however they are actually small philips screws, so IF they do ever fall out, they can simply be screwed back in! The other negative review stated that the stem broke. But that is one of the warnings it comes with, that the stem is "very fragile". As long as you don't overwind it, it shouldn't break. All in all, an excellent purchase for a fantastic timepiece!

reviewText: I waited almost one year to write this review since I feel it is necessary to really get to know a product before I give an opinion. Out of the box this watch was just OK. Yes it is plastic and to me that is not a problem but it has a black rubber wrist strap and that was the first thing I replaced. I recommend the Luminox Evo velcro strap as it fits perfect on this watch and is way more comfortable for everyday wear. I found the rubber strap to be hot and sweaty especially when I was out on the boat in the sun.For daily wear you will almost forget you are wearing it because it is so light. At least if you follow my advice and loose the rubber strap. The illuminated dial and hands are great for night time viewing. The watch also keeps excellent time. In almost one year it has failed to loose one minute! I can not say the same thing for my 3K cost Tag Heuer. The only issue I ever had with it was that I dropped it from the kitchen counter on the hardwood floor and the second hand jumped one second requiring the watch to be taken apart and the hand reset. I also have to say the crystal has held up very well to daily use. I have one very small scratch near the outside of the crystal that you have to look very hard to see.I would not hesitate to recommend this watch to anyone looking for a durable accurate inexpensive timepiece.
summary: Been a good watch for the money

title: Pyle Sports Snorkeling Master Watch
description: With this snorkeling watch from Pyle Sports, you’ll always be ready to handle the elements. The special dive-ready design provides water resistance up to 10 atmospheres — that’s 330 feet. The PSNKW30 reports your depth up to a resolution of 0.1 ft and is equipped with a dive alarm that activates when emerging faster than 6m per minute. The watch is also equipped with a thermometer to measure the temperature of the water to 1 degree Celsius or Fahrenheit. Best of all, all this data is stored in the dive log, which holds up to 100 records, including your time and date, dive duration, maximum dive depth, min. water temperature, and dive site indication. Electro-luminescent backlight means you’ll always know the time, day or night. Color: black.

reviewText: I've owned a Pebble since x-mas, and I really love it; however, I love it for the wrong reasons. This device is simply fun to own. At most I enjoy changing and creating watch faces for it. In fact, that's really the only thing I use it for. Imagine owning a device that you can change the look of at will. If you get bored of a watch face, you download or create a new one.Now, on to the actual functionality and usability of the Pebble. As of now, there's simply not enough usage for the Pebble. It doesn't allow much of any useful interaction between it and the smartphone outside using it to control song play on your smartphone. For example, you can receive text notifications, but you can't reply to them. It doesn't even have built-in generic responses such as, "okay," "see you later," etc. There are also a number of apps for weather and battery notifications, but many of the watch faces include that information. Again, the watch faces are really the highlight of this device. Recently they've been releasing games for the Pebble. I don't understand why, as it's awkward to play a game on your wrist, and the not to mention that the button are a bit flimsy and cheap feeling. I can see them popping off from repeatedly being pressed. It's also a bit buggy. There are times when for any reason at all you won't get notifications, weather updates, etc. and a bluetooth resync is in order.So why did I give this device 4 stars you ask? Because the cool watch faces make it worth buying. As stated above, many watch faces include information such as weather and battery status. The Pebble store has hundreds and possibly thousands of faces to choose from. Love Star Wars? There are tons of Star Wars watch faces. Love the look of a Rolex watch? There's a Rolex watch face in the store. You can even make your own watch faces if you can't find one of interest. The best part is that you don't have to be a programmer. There's a website called http://www.watchface-generator.de/ that allows you to create your own faces and upload them to your Pebble. I only pair the two to transfer watch faces, and I do find it useful to have on when I'm teaching in class and can't get to my phone.As a consumer, you have to decide what your looking for in a smart watch. If you want something that acts like a true smart device, then get the Samsung Gear, or whatever Apple releases for IOS. If you're looking for a cool fun watch with limited smart technology, then go with the Pebble.

reviewText: The watch mechanism itself is great, but if I can't wear it on my wrist, it's useless.  Although it looks good at first, the cheap plastic that holds the face to the strap gets worn out, stretches, and then eventually doesn't hold onto the face and buttons any longer.  I wear this watch only to the gym, so I put it on and take it off 4-5 times a week, which is apparently too much stress for the watch band.  Because the band is such an intricate part of the design-- the side buttons are incorporated into it-- it can't be replaced. I have to get a new watch.I've had $9.99 Casios that lasted 10 years... For $35, I think this watch should last a lot longer than the year or so I've gotten out of it.  Very poor design by Timex.  (Though very clever that this design flaw is not covered under the warranty.)  Two stars instead of 1 because it was a 5 star item for about 6 months.

reviewText: This is a well built, high quality, functional watch. I bought it because I like the 'Titanium' finish, and because I wanted a watch that could keep track of altitude, etc. If you calibrate your altitude periodically at places with known elevation, it makes for much more accurate readings. Because the watch determines altitude from barometric pressure, you need to re-calibrate with changes in the weather.If you need to resize the watch band, I would suggest going to a local jeweler and just paying a couple bucks to have them make the adjustments. There are YouTube videos that show how to do it, but I got halfway through and got stumped; so I paid the $7.50 to get it done by a professional (took them about 2 minutes).
title: Casio Protrek PAG240T-7 Altimeter Watch - Men's

The solar-powered Casio Protrek PAG240T-7 Altimeter Watch displays all the data you need to orient yourself and return back home unscathed. When trekking over countless mountain ridges or into desert canyons, this watch's digital altimeter, compass, thermometer, barometer, and clock ensure you can make informed decisions and stay safe in the wilderness.

reviewText: Within 2 weeks of using this watch the Indiglo (dial lighting) feature stopped working permanently.  That feature is one of the main reasons I bought this watch--so I can read the time in low light situations.  I was traveling outside the U.S. at the time, and continue to do so.  Repairing or replacing the watch while traveling overseas is costly--more time, trouble, and expense than it's worth.  Also, the wristband is already begin to unravel at the seams after just a few weeks of usage.  Timex' warranty information states the warranty is void if the watch wasn't purchased from an authorized dealer.  It appears the Amazon retailer I purchased this watch from is not an authorized dealer, so it wouldn't even help to make a claim for repair/replacement under the warranty.  More damaging than the lost money is being stuck with a defective watch that can't be easily fixed or replaced outside the U.S.  An overall disappointing purchase.
title: Timex Men's T48042 Expedition Digital Chrono Brown Nylon Strap Watch
description: Designed for active, outdoor lifestyles--as well as the rigors of harsh urban landscapes--the mid-sized Timex T48042 Expedition digital watch adds a stylish yet rugged complement to your everyday wear. It features a round resin watch case in black with an olive green top ring and a water-resistant leather strap in brown with black mesh lining. Timing features include a 100-hour chronograph with lap or split options, 99-lap counter, 24-hour countdown timer, and second time zone with date. It also offers three alarms with daily, weekday, and weekend options, and water resistance to 100 meters (330 feet).The Indiglo night-light uniformly lights the surface of the watch dial using patented blue electroluminescent lighting technology. It uses less battery power than most other watch illumination systems, enabling your watch battery to last longer. The Night Mode feature allows you to illuminate the Indiglo night-light for 3 seconds with any button press, regardless of the mode or function.

reviewText: I was very pleased with the results I got from this chronograph. I took it out into the woods and set it up. It was a moderately sunny day, and there were tree limbs overhead, but using the provided sunshades it gave me consistent results for loads out of my Marlin 1894 in .357 Magnum from about 15 feet away. They were also pretty much in-line with what my reloading manual said they should be, so I am pretty confident in the accuracy of the readings as well.I then switched to the same loads out of my 2-inch snubby revolver, and got errors from the first two shots...not too surprising to me considering the muzzle blast out of the snubby is pretty ridiculous. I backed up a few feet and it began registering the shots successfully. Then I let one of my rounds stray a bit to the left and hit one of the rods for the sunshade support. The sunshade went flying, but was unbroken. The rod was bent into a "u", but I straightened it out in my vise when I got home, and it's (almost) as good as new. I know there have been some complaints on here about the flimsiness of the sunshade, but you will be happy for that if you hit it...it keeps stuff from getting broken.Overall, I'm very pleased with this product. I did a significant amount of research before purchasing, because I'd read a lot of frustrated comments regarding chronographs in general. I didn't want to go cheap and get junk, but I didn't want to spend a bunch of money for something that didn't work any better than the cheaper option, either. I was very pleased with the results that I got from the chrony, especially considering that is is pretty much the cheapest option out there. When I did my part and put the rounds where they were supposed to go, it delivered accurate, consistent results. Great product...just don't expect it to be bulletproof :-).
