title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

reviewText: I purchased this watch as a replacement for one that I've worn for the past 2 years. I tend to be rough on watches, so I like that I can buy a decent watch that can take a little abuse... Since this was the exact same model as the last 3 I've owned, I assumed all would be well with it. I was wrong, as soon as I opened the package, I noticed that the cover over the face had some odd defects in it, but since I don't wear it for the looks, I just shrugged it off and wore it... After less than 3 months of owning this, we went to Niagara Falls on the Maid of the Mist. Since the watch has always been waterproof, and still claims to be, I never gave it a second thought that it might get wet. Once we got off of the boat, I immediately noticed that there was water under the glass and the backlight had quit working... As soon as I got home, I filled out a Timex Warranty replacement form online and sent it off... $12 later, they sent me a new watch, which so far has been much better, but I'm still out $12, which is almost 50% of what I paid for the watch to begin with... Lesson learned, today's quality is far less than what it used to be.

reviewText: The Chrony F-1 works as intended. It even tells you when you what the fault is when it cannot register your shot.One set of examples, when I was shooting skewed and the Chrony was not able to calculate the FPS of that shot it told me that it was because the 2nd sensor did not see the shot. I tried to correct and I got it's sister message, one that tells me that the Chrony's 1st sensor did not see the shot. Make sure you shoot straight down the middle is the lesson here.If you should use it indoors, such as for airguns, use incandescent lights, otherwise the Chrony will not see the shot (this is mentioned in the instruction manual).I think I will want to upgrade my F-1 by getting the Chrony Ballistic Printer, which will crunch numbers for me too.Word of caution, do not shoot too close to the Chrony, especially with the larger calibers (>=7.62mm/.300") or magnums, the muzzle blast will scar the face of the Chrony and provide you with a cool "ping" sound. This all will likely cause an inaccurate readout, if not damage your Chrony.

reviewText: Last October someone gave me a pair of slip-on house slippers that were purchased from a big box chain store. Two weeks later, those shoes caused me to fall in the kitchen and fracture my neck. reviewText: This was the first MBT style I purchased. The Lami's were a perfect fit for me. I have worn several styles of MBTs and these remain my favorite in fit and appearance! I wish MBT would manufacture this style again....  I love the black & grey with the hot pink accents! Fun and pretty. I would love to purchase another pair in the right size (I wore mine to death!!)...A word of caution: MBTs are fabulous for walking. They are incredibly comfortable, make your walking movement/strides actually smoother & effortless, realign your skeletal system, and relieve foot/joint pain and discomfort; HOWEVER, the same cannot be said when standing or taking limited strides for extended period of time. I frequently lead week-long work groups and stand/walk within a confined space for hours at a time. My feet where hurting so much in my beloved MBTs that I went sock-footed and then started bringing a second non-MBT pair of shoes to change into 1/2 way through the day. So remember - These shoes were made for walkin' (not standing around!!)In my experience the most frustrating thing with MBT is that no two styles fit the same. Since there are no MBT retailers near me, I have ended up with a few pair that I might not have purchased...  or might have needed to adjust by a 1/2 size. I also tried ordering some through a non-Amazon site (at great prices)...  but one pair looked really cheap and were much too small, the other (Lami) were the same size as my original, but much too loose. Both of these 'bargain' pair appeared to be seconds and actually arrived from China - though the websites looked legit. So just a word of caution....  buy these through Amazon or a reputable, well-known site. If you find prices elsewhere that look too good to be true.....  they probably are!! Craigslist here I come - I cannot return them to China!!  LOL
summary: These shoes were made for walkin' ......

reviewText: I didn't know what to expect with this watch.  I found it when I was looking at Runkeeper, an app for tracking workouts on my phone.  I really wanted to monitor my heart rate during a workout, which is why I bought this 'watch'.  So far that's about the only thing I haven't been able to see on my wrist that I'd want.  I installed 'Glance' which is awesome, turns your watch into a quick summary of time, weather, unchecked email, txt messages, and vm's... very neatly and clearly.. oh, and it tells me the percent of battery on my phone.I received it and had it working within a few minutes.  I'm reasonably technical but I'm new to the Android world.  I'm connected with my Samsung S4.  It all works just fine.  I lost connection once but I think it was because I changed a lot of settings in the Glance app and it needed to reconnect to apply them... I don't know.Using it with Runkeeper is an analysts dream.  GPS tracks your route, you have goals, charts, graphs, real-time performance, feedback, etc.  And, on my phone I can see my heart rate.. I haven't figured out how to get a warning when I get to (or exceed) my target heart rate though.  I'm sure there's a setting, I just haven't found it.  (I'm using a Polar bluetooth HRM that sends my HR via Bluetooth to the phone, in the Runkeeper app.)I use this in my office where I am in sessions with people and it's nice to just get a quick buzz that someone has texted me... and I can ignore all but emergencies.  It vibrates like the phone when someone is calling, so it's not super quiet if it's buzzing on a desk.. but pretty quiet/discreet on your wrist.  I also see emails and can read them.With Glance there are some pre-programmed text messages you can send people... "on my way, OK, sounds good... etc." and you can add your own... Like, "I'm leaving the office, hope to be home for dinner soon."Without Glance, this is really a 1-way extension of what's on your phone with a few watch faces.  There are a good number of applications that make this watch useful to a wide variety of needs.  So far it has exceeded mine other than the heart rate thing.It's good for someone who doesn't want to keep looking at their phone or stay tethered to it.  If nothing else, I get piece of mind knowing I'll get a quick buzz on my wrist if something comes up while I've put my phone down for an extended amount of time.  Which for me is often.. Definitely worth $150 for me... it's already helped me a lot... and I've only had it 2 days.Quality-wise it's 'ok'.  It's a normal-looking watch but it is plastic.  It looks like it'll be outdated in a year.  I have a feeling it'll get a little more refined as the company gets more profit.  I look forward to it.  I'll wear this one till it wears out.  Oh, and it has a 1-yr warranty which is pretty awesome for this kind of thing.------ Update: About 5 days after getting the watch... I looked everywhere for a battery meter, there isn't one - until it starts to go down, and it's only visible when you're looking through the menus of the watch.  So, when you get your watch, charge it, and find there is no indicator, that's because you're OK, it doesn't need a charge yet.  I now have the standard battery icon in the top right of the screen.  So, I expect it'll last another day or 2, about a week on 1 charge as advertised... and I've played around with it a lot.I'm still enjoying it as much as day 1.  :)

The iRobot is a cute little Two-Wheel robot controlled with your iPhone, iPad, or iPod Touch. It combines infrared control technology with steam punk design thanks to its exposed internal gears and working. The iRobot receives command signal from your idevice then perform various movement including left/right turn, backward/forward, or acceleration. It's a toy that kids (or you) can play with for hours. 
 The iRobot is made with hardened acrylic and robustly built. The outer and internal wheels are in white color, while the body of the robot is transparent. When turned on, the eyes of the iRobot will light up in soft blue LED light, adding to the iRobot the mysterious touch of an Alien. reviewText: Great watch! Have all the required and needed gadgets for work and adventure! Defenitely a must have for any person!
title: Suunto Core Black Military
description: Building on the success of the venerable Suunto Vector, the Suunto Core keeps you informed of conditions while you hike, bike, or camp, making it a terrific companion for outdoor enthusiasts of all stripes. What can the Suunto Core do for you? For starters, it can sense an approaching squall even when the sky looks clear. This intelligent Storm Alarm--one of several intelligent features designed to keep you safe and secure--is activated by a rapid drop in air pressure over a three-hour period. Once the Core senses the change, the Storm Alarm sounds and flashes, letting you know that something unpleasant is fast approaching. The built-in altimeter, meanwhile, displays your current elevation, shows how much you've climbed or descended, and records your entire session for later analysis. Accurate to within 30,000 feet, the altimeter is an extremely valuable tool for mountaineering, backcountry skiing, and wilderness travel. Add in such features as a barometer, a digital thermometer, a weather trend indicator, and a digital compass and you have a terrific wrist-top computer for almost all your outdoor needs. Additional features include several traditional watch functions, including dual times, a date display, and an alarm; predicted times for sunrise and sunset to help you maximize your daylight hours; an automatic Alti/Baro mode that senses movement or lack thereof and switches between the altimeter and barometer accordingly; a depth meter that provides accurate water depth readings to 30 feet; and the ability to function in English, German, French, and Spanish. The Suunto Core carries a two-year warranty.

reviewText: I have a couple of goats and some chickens and I used to wear an old pair of sneakers out to the barn every morning to do chores.  There is always dew on the grass and it rains here all the time and the sneakers were always wet, smelly and caked with chicken poop and mud on the bottom.  These shoes are great!  I can slip them on when my hands are full, they are fully waterproof, they hose down when the bottoms are caked with dirt, they have a removable lining and they're pretty comfortable.  They are somewhat loose relative to the length, which is why I only gave them 4 stars.  I wear a size 8 1/2, but the 8 would have been too short.  I ordered a 9, which fits length-wise, but is pretty wide. I have a narrow foot, but I also wear an arch support so I am able to easily fit them under the removable lining to give added comfort and support to my feet.  The soles are sturdy on the stones and uneven ground in the pasture.  They seem like they will hold up well, but they are so low cost that I won't be upset if I have to buy another pair next year.  Plus, they are made in the US.  They claim to have a recycling program for worn out sloggers, but I couldn't see any information about it on their web site.  Overall, a great purchase if you need a pair of inexpensive, easy-on shoes for chores around the yard.
summary: Great slip-on shoe for doing chores

reviewText: Got my safety cat today. It's a tad smaller than I expected it to be, but fits nicely in the hand--any bigger and it would probably be too unwieldly. What's more, it's heavy for its size; this is a sturdy little gadget. I don't think it will ever break.I'm honestly not sure how effective this would be in a fight. It likely depends on the person using it. The main advantage of the safety cat, I think (other than discretion--who would ever guess this is a weapon?) is that you won't forget you have it on you. If, say, I carried a knife in my bag/pocket (I don't), I don't think I would have the presence of mind to dig it out in the event that I needed it. The safety cat goes on your keyring, and you carry your keys, so you constantly see it and it's constantly ready for action. All you have to do is get your fingers through the holes and PUNCH!There is no doubt in my mind that it would hurt like hell to get hit with this thing. The points on the ears aren't sharp (so you won't accidentally nick yourself) but they *might* be able to break skin with enough force behind them. Also, the description says that the ears have been strategically distanced so that they can effectively hit the eyes. I'm not sure I would have the heart to purposely get somebody in the eyes with this, even a mugger. Plus, I'm afraid I might get sued if I permanently blind somebody. (Although they won't have gotten a very good look at me, amirite?) I'm not sure of the legal status of this thing in my area, but who cares? Like I said, no one would ever guess this is a weapon. I guess I'll just have to wait to find out what the law says until after I nail somebody with it.All in all, I didn't buy this because I was looking for a serious defense weapon. I just saw it and thought, "Wow, that's really cool! Wow, only five dollars! *BUY*" So, shame on me. It's a great conversation piece at the very least; all my friends LOVED it and want one now. But who knows? One day it might end up saving my life. If I were a sensible girl, I might say something along the lines of, "Gee, I hope I don't ever get the chance to test this!" But in complete honesty... I do. I do, indeed. I look forward to it.
title: Safety Cat Women's Self Defense Keychain - Teal
description:
IMPORTANT: When Flying Pack in Check-in Luggage Only!
The Safety Cat is a self defense, personal protection tool designed mainly for women. As women we are told for safety reasons to have our keys in our hands as we go to and from our cars. Many of us even hold our keys between our fingers walking through parking lots or out doing errands so we will be able to fight off an attacker. Unfortunately, that can be cumbersome and awkward. If you're in the position of fighting off an attacker the keys may shift in your hand making it difficult for the fight to continue. The Safety Cat self defense keychain will eliminate this problem. When holding the Safety Cat, your two fingers will be placed in the eyes of the cat and the face of the cat will rest securely in the palm of your hand. The smooth, sleek design of the Safety Cat will feel very comfortable in your hand and you will be able to grasp it firmly. Remember, the Safety Cat is used for self defense purposes only, but if you're fighting for your life the unique design of the Safety Cat is made for striking at the eyes of your attacker or attacking any fleshy part of the body.

reviewText: I have been looking at boots and my biggest complaint is how thin and low quality the fashion boots are. I took a chance and ordered these Amazon and am pleasantly surprised. The leather is firm but not overly stiff. These are fairly comfortable out of the box. If you want a good looking, casual and edgy boot...or if you actually want to ride a motorcycle ....this is a great boot.I am giving this boot five stars because based on price and description, they fit the bill. I ordered these in my normal running shoe size - 8.5. The foot fits perfectly. I will say that I have wide feet and these fit my foot so well, you'd think I ordered wide width. So keep that in mind. The shaft is liberal in the ankle and such, probably because gals with thinner legs can opt to tuck their pants in. I, however, have very muscular calves. I knew the shaft would be too narrow at the very top and I need an extra inch or so. It's not the boots that are the problem...and for not being a wide shaft boot, I'm kind of surprised I can pull these on. I can wear them with pants, but my husband does a bit of leather work and he is going to make another split on the inside of the boot so I cam get the extra inch or so. I feel it would still be worth it to keep them.I've been wearing these for about a half hour inside and I feel them easily stretching a bit so breaking them in will be easy. I'm really happy with.this purchase. I knew it would be tough to find cool motorcycle boots to fit my calves, but this is pretty darn close with real leather and functionality without being too heavy.

reviewText: This shoes fitted so well and feet felt great. Oh yeah, it looked great too! I just hope Giro would produce same shoe in velcro straps which are easier to put on.
title: Giro Empire Shoes
description: In the perpetual circle that we call life, we're constantly confronted with the 'old' becoming 'new' as the 'new' becomes outdated. And in the instance of cycling shoes, the lace-up closure of the Giro Empire Shoes is the new now. However, this isn't to say that the Empire is a novelty -- far from it. The shoes were actually designed at the behest of the young American prodigy, Taylor Phinney, for the 2012 Giro and Summer Games. The rationale behind the Empire is simple -- utilizing the versatile fit adjustment and low weight of laces provides the ultimate balance of comfort and power. When you think about it, no hook-and-loop or ratcheting buckle closure system can match the mathematical possibilities for a lace's volume customization. Through varying lacing patterns or tensions, you can customize the medial or lateral pull, or the tightness at the forefoot or instep, all at the same time. But, if you're anything like us, your first nagging thought concerns the laces getting caught in the drivetrain -- you're not alone. However, Giro's one step ahead of us, and accordingly, it incorporated a retaining lace garage on the tongue of the shoes. So, the retention system provides a positive conformity with the foot at a fraction of the typical weight. And while the Empire's laces are an obvious differentiator, so are its other design features. Starting at the uppers themselves, Giro wrapped the Empire with one-piece of Tejin microfiber. This contributes to the shoes' sleek profile, but it also reduces weight while the fabric selection increases breathability. That's right, the Japanese Tejin fabric is extremely lightweight and highly breathable. Furthermore, Giro placed focused points of perforation along the Empire's sides and tongue in order to increase airflow throughout the shoe. And in case it gets a little sweaty inside, the Empire also features an X-Static footbed that's anti-microbial, anti-stink, and anti-static.

reviewText: Dear Amazon Shopper,This wallet is a tankish monstrosity, the greatest strength of which is simultaneously its only real weakness.  Before I get into the shortcoming of this wallet, however, let me just cover the basics.You're probably looking at this wallet because you want something durable that holds stuff.  Well friend, if that's the case, you've come to the right page.  The nylon is over-strength, the seams are overstitched, and the construction is generally overengineered; unless you're using this wallet to play tug-of-war with your German Shepherd, I suspect it will last a very long time.  In terms of capacity, this wallet will hold your cash, cards, and change, and has interior and exterior transparent sleeves for ID's.  If your current wallet holds it, this wallet will hold it, and then some.However, there's no guarantee that your pocket will hold this wallet.  One of the persons to whom I gifted this behemoth ultimately opted not to use it, after discovering that the wallet would not fit into his back pocket (neither when empty nor when full).  As such, I recommend this wallet for persons who opt to carry it on a belt, as carrying it in a back pocket is only viable if your pockets are very large.The bottom line: a cavernous wallet layered in nylon armor at the expense of form-factor.Thank you

reviewText: My family and I have four Timex Ironman watches among us.  One by one these things have stopped being waterproof.At first they are fantastic (thus, the number of them that we own).  The features are great and they are waterproof - for a while.  None of these has ever been abused, just worn and never in water deeper than 10 feet (a mere 3.3 meters).  One of them, worn into a swimming pool, came out full of water and completely non-functional.  Fortunately it was under warranty, but it still cost $7 to have repaired/replaced.  Two others are older than one year, but less than two, and have started becoming foggy after swimming (pool, not ocean).  The fog evaporates after an hour or so, indicating that water can not only get in, but that it can get out.  The last is only six months old and fine so far, but I do not expect it to last much longer--it too will likely leak just after the warranty expires.For the cost of these things and the claim that they are "waterproof to 100 m," they are incredibly unreliable long-term.

reviewText: I have owned a Dynamic chainless bike for about three years and I decided to try Sonoma's chainless women's bike for my girlfriend.  On the plus side it is about two-hundred dollars less than Dynamic's and it rides nice enough.  On the negative side, it is a little heavier than Dynamic's and Sonoma uses poor quality parts.  Like the brake handles and cables are very cheap and of poor quality.  The large bearing at the top of the fork is rough and it was originally so tight that it was difficult to turn the wheel.  I had to re-adjust it.  The gear shift cable needed to be adjusted in order to get the gears to shift smoothly and there wasn't any grease on the drive gear at the back wheel.  The tube in the front tire was pinched between the wheel and the tire, putting a big hole in it.  Had to replace the tube.  I don't know yet how well the bike will hold up, since I just got it all together today.  I really like the chainless drive system, but the rest of the bike is nothing special and in fact looks and feels rather cheap.  For the price I would expect better quality control and better quality parts.  So I think that the most I can give it is 3 stars.  It is chainless and rides nice, but it is of poor quality and may not hold up.
title: Sonoma Women's Chainless Drive Evolution Urban Voyager Bicycle
description: A fashionable, reliable way to join cycling's chainless uprising, the Sonoma Urban Voyager chainless women's bicycle offers great looks and an even better ride. At first glance, riders will be intrigued by the Urban Voyager's sophisticated design. The bike packs a host of cutting-edge features into its sleek, streamlined body, including a lightweight aluminum frame that makes parking or loading the bike onto a car or bus a breeze. Specifically engineered to make navigating urban or suburban environments simpler and safer, the Urban Voyager also includes an ergonomically designed seat that helps you stay comfortable on long rides, adjustable alloy handlebars, ergonomically designed hand grips, pull-lever front and rear alloy brakes, and a shock-absorbing suspension fork that ensures a smoother, more controlled ride.The bike's chainless D-Drive system eliminates the trouble-causing chain and derailleur.Sonoma's Chainless D-Drive SystemIt's the low-maintenance chainless design that really stands out, however. Powering the newest trend in chainless bicycling, the chainless D-Drive system replaces the parts of a bike that cause the most problems--the chain and derailleur. In their place, the D-Drive system uses a drive shaft with a fully enclosed bevel gear system to transmit power from the bike pedals to the rear wheel. Shimano internal gears within the rear wheel help the system run smoothly and quietly while optimizing pedal efficiency. At the same time, the Shimano "twist and go" gear system is responsive and easy to use, so you can shift with the flick of a finger.The chainless D-Drive system offers a number of benefits over traditional chain bikes. In addition to delivering a much quieter ride, it keeps you from ruining your favorite clothes while riding to work or getting grease all over your hands while fixing a slipped chain. The D-Drive system is also protected from external elements, so it doesn't require the ongoing cleaning, lubrication, and checkups that a chain-drive bike typically requires. And the internal drive shaft is less likely to sustain damage from falls and road debris, giving it a significantly longer life than a chain. In fact, the D-Drive system carries a warranty that lasts for the life of your bike. Once you experience Sonoma's exclusive D-Drive chainless system, you may never want to ride a chain-driven bicycle again.Other features include built-in water bottle mounts, a convenient rear carrier rack, and 700c Kenda city tread tires and tubes. Best of all, everything on the bike is backed by either a two-year or lifetime warranty. The Sonoma Urban Voyager is available in a light satin sky color with subtle grey accents.The bright Shimano auto-light system includes a Xenon bulb.Riders will love the convenient rear carrier rack.SpecificationsColor: Light satin sky with grey accentsFrame size: 19 inchesWheel size: 28 inchesFrame: Lightweight 6000 series aluminum with water bottle mountsSaddle: Cionlli dual fabric commuter saddleHandlebars: Alloy with adjustable stemFork: RST SOFI ML suspension with mechanical lockout systemFenders: Quick-release front and rearHub: Shimano Nexus Inter 7 (rear), 7-speed sealed gear hubShifter: Shimano Nexus Revoshift 7-speedBrakes: Front and rear alloy V-brakes with alloy hand pull leversOperating system: D-Drive chainlessRims: 700c double-wall alloySeat post: Alloy with quick-release lever adjustmentRack: Alloy rear rack with Sonoma signature storage bagTires: 700c Kenda city tread tires and tubesPedals: Plastic platform, 9/16 inches, with CPSC reflectorsGrips: Anatomically designed dual-densityStand-over height: 25-1/2 inchesWarranties: Lifetime on frame, fork, and D-Drive system, 2 years on all other componentsAbout Dynacraft BicyclesDynacraft brings families together by providing affordable, high-quality bicycles for everyone in the family, no matter their age. Based in American Canyon, California, Dynacraft imports and distributes such brands as Barbie, Dekra, Hot Wheels, Magna, Malibu, Next, and Rhino. The company's recent innovations include a new state-of-the-art distribution center in Napa, California, that reduces the time it takes to get Dynacraft's bikes to customers' stores. Dynacraft also entered the adult comfort bike segment by introducing the Dekra D-Drive, a chainless three-speed bike specifically designed for pleasure riding.

reviewText: Just got the Pebble this morning.  Setup was a breeze with my iPhone running iOS 7.  I read most of the reviews here on Amazon before buying the watch, and it looks like some of the doubters either received defective Pebbles or were just plain wrong.  The high points:Build Quality - my Pebble has no discernible manufacturing defects in the watch casing, as some others have observed with their Pebbles.  If you bought a Pebble from Amazon and there are nicks, scratches, or other defects in the watch casing, just send it back and get another one.  That's why we buy from Amazon people.  Easy returns and exchanges.Setup - I am into tech, but I did not have to draw on any serious knowledge of technology to set this thing up.  The Pebble folks have done a great job in making sure users are spoon-fed by the Pebble app and the watch during setup.  It.Was.Easy.Exchange Notifications - I read in some other reviews that users were upset that the Pebble purportedly does not receive email notifications from Microsoft Exchange accounts.  This is simply not true if you are using an iPhone running iOS 7.  I am receiving my work emails (Exchange server) just fine.  I do not have an Android phone, so if there is a problem there, I leave that to someone else to address.  But as to reviews claiming that iPhones with iOS 7 cannot receive Microsoft Exchange email notifications, THEY ARE FLAT OUT WRONG.Strap - I ordered a nicer replacement strap when I ordered my Pebble.  Replacing the strap was incredibly easy, and all I had to do was Google "replace Pebble watch strap" and view a short video.  The watch looks much nicer with the replacement strap.Slickwrap - I also ordered an Onyx brushed metal wrap for my Pebble.  Application took a little while to get right, but it was worth it.  Makes the watch look great.  IMPORTANT - the Slickwrap came with a screen protector film, which is a MUST with the Pebble.  The Pebble has a plastic screen that is very prone to scratching.  Applying a screen protector should be pretty much the first thing you do with your Pebble.I love the Pebble so far because it is exactly what I expected it to be - a device to, among other things, receive notifications from my iPhone and control my iPhone's music.  With the coming 2.0 firmware update, the watch is going to be able to do even more than that.  Right now I am running the SmartModernMod - Button Mod watch face from MyPebbleFaces.com, and it is very cool.  Weather, calendar, notifications, music control, etc.If you are looking for a second smartphone to wear on your wrist, then the Pebble is not for you.  That said, even now, Pebble does a lot more than just provide smartphone notifications, and the 2.0 firmware update is going to open things up for exciting developments in the future.  I am also looking forward to the GoPro Pebble app, as I have used my GoPro to video my younger son's tournament baseball games for years, and since I also manage his team, this will make it easier to turn the camera on and off between innings and let me focus on the game.In short, read the reviews, watch the videos, and read the information on Pebble's website.  If all of that describes a smartwatch that fits your needs and desires, then you will not be disappointing.

reviewText: I bought this GPS on deal elsewhere. I was surprised by it being so deeply discounted being such a recent launch.After a couple of weeks using it I can see why.They propose a simple, no gimmick, product. The problem is that the user interface simply makes no sense.First, you have to active the GPS on every mode you use it. For instance, if you hold a button for a couple of seconds, it reads "GPS ON" but then you go to Bike mode and it blinks "Indoor", so you have to turn it on again (and every time you go to bike mode).As an occasional rider, I just want to know my speed and how much I rode. I assumed it would start measuring both automatically and pause when I stop. It doesn't.You have to go to the Chrono mode, start the chronograph, then go back to Bike mode and start the GPS again.Given that the GPS seems to turn itself off so often, I assumed that I didn't need to do anything once I was done riding my bike. Wrong again.The battery completely depleted in about 24 hours. I searched a forum and they said I had to hold the button that turns the GPS on/off for a couple of seconds so it turns itself off. By doing this, now it lasts many days in stand by mode.And also the manual is almost useless.How could they make something they claim to be simple so complicated?They have the chance to solve these issues, and improve the unit, with firmware updates. I asked them and they said they will. I hope it happens.

With our new GPS Draft we can help you make the most of every workout.Simple to use, GPS Draft houses a high sensitivity GPS receiver that allows you to track your journey alongside a USB data upload cable that allows you to easily upload to your workouts.30 ride files storage, current/average/max speed calculations, auto calendar, and 5 programmable alarms make sure you never forget where you have been. reviewText: I am only giving one star because that is the minimum.  I can not express my outrage and disappointment with how Pebble has treated those dedicated potential customers that placed a pre-order on their website.  I placed a pre-order on Pebble's web site 5 months ago for a basic black watch and never received it but, at this point, I do not want one whether it is the best product in the world or not.  I do not want one nor care about ever having one.They have put us pre-order customers off for all of these months now (and would not even provide an estimated ship date) and just a few minutes ago I see that they are shipping basic black Pebble watches to be sold in stores at Best Buy in 5 days.  What was the purpose of offering the pre-orders 6 months ago?I am sorry but I thought I needed to document this horrible treatment to customers by this company.  If we think of other companies that do not treat their customers very well (for example, a well-known PC operating system provider) this is something that becomes an ingrained culture within that company.  I hope that Pebble does not continue to treat its customers this way for their sake, but they have lost a once-enthusiastic one.

Timing features include a 100-hour chronograph with lap or split options, 99-lap counter, 24-hour countdown timer, and second time zone with date. I was really dissappointed when I opened the package & saw that they were bright yellow with a pic of Belle on the toes that didn't even look nice with the florecnet material. Now it said ballet slippers-they are not ballet slippers! They aren't even slippers there is no lining or cushion or anything inside & the seem irrites my daughters foot & she either needs to put socks on or just takes them off. Also they are huge, now I didn't see a sizing when I ordered them so I figured they'd be a little big but she's be able to grow into them...they are so big that she can barley play in them. It will take her several years to grow into them. I would not recommend ordering these shoes.I could have made a pair nicer than these! Not worth my $9.

The "AM" could not light up.How to set the brightness:Just press the down setting button several times, when upper speedometer's light is on at "2 6 10 11" and the 1-4 number button is on, then press the down button to set the brightness grade (1-4 grade).How to set the auto timing light up:Press the down setting button several times, when the down speedometer lights up at "ON/OFF" and a number at left side, set a time you like the LED automatically lights up from every 5 to 30 minutes. reviewText: I love this smart watch!!! I have had it now for two weeks. It was at first difficult to pair my android to my phone but I soon found out it was an easy fix. I turned off my phone, turned it back on turned on the blue tooth to my phone and paired my phone to my watch first before I ran the pebble app.I love how I can get texts, emails, calendar reminders. I can check the news with rss feeds with my pebble, the weather, it's water proof, I can change my music, set timers and alarms. I never have to buy an actual battery for it since you charge the watch like a phone. Although, I had to buy a charger for it since the watch itself did not come with one. I also love how you can change the face of the watches as many times as you want. I currently have 3 games on it too, like some worm game, etch-e-sketch (pebble-sketch) and Pong.All around this is a great watch. If I had to give one complaint I would say that when you are switching between watch faces, the watch numbers get small and kind of stop until the watch resets itself with is not all the time but it does happen from time to time. The reset can take a min. The other thing that is a bit annoying is that if you get spam you will start to get it on your wrist but so what it's a smart watch and I take it off at night so it's not buzzing on my wrist to wake me up. I would recommend this watch, it's a neat toy to have.
summary: Pebble Smart Watch Pretty Smart on the road to Very

reviewText: The Timex Men's T5K608 is an absolutely excellent watch in most regards and at just under $30 a great bargain, but overly sensitive buttons were a deal killer for me.On the positive side- This is an incredibly comfortable watch to wear. Not only is it super light, but Timex has done a simply brilliant job with the band.- The numbers are big and easy to read- The backlighting works well- The watch looks good- Having an extra time zone available at the push of a button is a major convenienceHowever... The buttons are very sensitive and not recessed so if you are active, or wear the watch while sleeping, you may find it switched to a different mode. I've awoken to find the watch showing Japan time and looked down while doing an obstacle course to see the watch had switched itself to a countdown mode.I wanted to love the Ironman but ended up returning it and getting aCasio Men's DW5600E-1V G-Shock Classic Digital Watch, a roughly comparable watch. The G-Shock is $10 more, lacks the two time zones, has smaller (though perfectly legible numbers) and wasn't as immediately comfortable as the Timex. However, its buttons are recessed and stiff so there is little chance it will put itself into the wrong mode, and I get the sense that it is a generally more solid, shock and wear resistant watch. Much as I liked aspects of the Timex, the Casio is a better watch for me.
summary: Excellent Watch Marred By Overly Sensitive Buttons

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

title: Suunto X-Lander Wrist-Top Computer Watch with Altimeter, Barometer, Compass, and Chronograph
description: The ultimate option for the outdoor enthusiast, the silver Suunto X-Lander wrist-top computer offers an accurate altimeter, a complete barometer, a precise electronic compass, and a multifunction sports watch in a single elegant package. Regardless of your excursion--whether it's climbing mountains, riding a muddy bike track, or skiing off piste--you need accurate, real-time information about your surroundings to pull off a successful trip. The X-Lander contributes by not only providing important data, but also keeping track of your activities so you can make rational decisions at key moments. In addition, the watch is user-friendly and solidly built, with a non-allergenic aluminum casing, a carbon-fiber back, a durable mineral crystal glass, and a water-resistant fabric strap.The built-in altimeter, which boasts a range of up to 29,500 feet, puts all 14 of the world's 8,000-plus-meter summits within the avid climber's range. Among the altimeter's functions are an altitude measurement function that lets you follow the vertical progress between stages, an automatic 24-hour memory that stores the altitude and ascent/decent rate for every hour, and an adjustable altitude alarm. Climbers will also dig the logbook function, which lets you record total and cumulative vertical ascents and descents as well as the number of runs skied.The X-Lander also displays the current barometric pressure and temperature--a must for activities in which weather plays a factor. The device automatically records barometric data for the previous four days, with the first six hours manifested in one-hour intervals and the rest in six-hour intervals. When the reference altitude is set correctly, the instrument also displays the present sea level pressure, which makes it easier to read and understand the barometric pressure at high altitudes.And few things are more important when exploring unfamiliar territory than a compass. The X-Lander's electronic compass contributes by guiding you with cardinal or half- cardinal points and a North-South arrow. The compass can also be set to track a certain bearing, which helps you follow a chosen direction. Meanwhile, the unit's declination adjustment function allows you to correct the difference between true North and magnetic North.In addition to the variety of outdoor functions, the X-Lander also displays normal time, with such add-ons as three daily alarms, a calendar programmed to the year 2089, a stopwatch with split-time measurement, and a countdown timer. Other features include a durable negative LCD display, a user-replaceable battery, and water-resistance to 100 feet. The X-Lander is backed by a two-year warranty on parts and labor.What's in the Box?X-Lander wrist-top computer, battery, user's manual.

reviewText: these fit the replacement bill nicely. my beloved froog togg hogg toggs pants (bought for jacket color- reg yellow) started to leak on one knee/leg (2 years old used several times a year & i could never find the hole,) plus i hated the bulky buckle, the bottom elastic stirrups wouldn't stay snapped, & the bottom velcro was a nuisance (i kind of hate velcro...) so i searched frogg togg site to make sure of measurements. i'm 5'2 & 114# plus i tried a small on in a local store that fit well, BUT i ordered large purely for the length of inseam since the last ones had a tendency to pull up over the tops of my 10" tingly's while sitting on the motorcycle. so these are definitely too big, but so were the last (men's small) and i got used to it... this inseam is actually longer than the men's small by 3" which is what was important to me. i much prefer this small easy toggle belt closure, and lack of velcro on bottom legs that catch on everything, just a nice simple zipper that is plenty long... have not had them in severe relentless rain yet (thankfully) but if the zips leak i'll update. frogg toggs are less hot & less smelly than rubber backed or other fibers, but you do have to watch hot pipes! they sell a patch protector for that but i have yet to try to adhere some on last or these~ one day!

reviewText: I really like the style of these watches and have bought several because I can't find anything else similar - but they seem to be very poor quality and don't last long. title: Suunto X-Lander Wrist-Top Computer Watch with Altimeter, Barometer, Compass, and Chronograph
description: The ultimate option for the outdoor enthusiast, the silver Suunto X-Lander wrist-top computer offers an accurate altimeter, a complete barometer, a precise electronic compass, and a multifunction sports watch in a single elegant package. Regardless of your excursion--whether it's climbing mountains, riding a muddy bike track, or skiing off piste--you need accurate, real-time information about your surroundings to pull off a successful trip. The X-Lander contributes by not only providing important data, but also keeping track of your activities so you can make rational decisions at key moments. In addition, the watch is user-friendly and solidly built, with a non-allergenic aluminum casing, a carbon-fiber back, a durable mineral crystal glass, and a water-resistant fabric strap.The built-in altimeter, which boasts a range of up to 29,500 feet, puts all 14 of the world's 8,000-plus-meter summits within the avid climber's range. Among the altimeter's functions are an altitude measurement function that lets you follow the vertical progress between stages, an automatic 24-hour memory that stores the altitude and ascent/decent rate for every hour, and an adjustable altitude alarm. Climbers will also dig the logbook function, which lets you record total and cumulative vertical ascents and descents as well as the number of runs skied.The X-Lander also displays the current barometric pressure and temperature--a must for activities in which weather plays a factor. The device automatically records barometric data for the previous four days, with the first six hours manifested in one-hour intervals and the rest in six-hour intervals. When the reference altitude is set correctly, the instrument also displays the present sea level pressure, which makes it easier to read and understand the barometric pressure at high altitudes.And few things are more important when exploring unfamiliar territory than a compass. The X-Lander's electronic compass contributes by guiding you with cardinal or half- cardinal points and a North-South arrow. The compass can also be set to track a certain bearing, which helps you follow a chosen direction. Meanwhile, the unit's declination adjustment function allows you to correct the difference between true North and magnetic North.In addition to the variety of outdoor functions, the X-Lander also displays normal time, with such add-ons as three daily alarms, a calendar programmed to the year 2089, a stopwatch with split-time measurement, and a countdown timer. Other features include a durable negative LCD display, a user-replaceable battery, and water-resistance to 100 feet. The X-Lander is backed by a two-year warranty on parts and labor.What's in the Box?X-Lander wrist-top computer, battery, user's manual.

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

reviewText: My sister bought me this watch for my birthday, about three months ago.  Since then I have been able to use it for a total of 3 weeks.  For starters, even while it worked, it was extremely buggy - frequently dropping its connection to my phone, randomly dropping texts - totally unreliable for anything other than telling the time.  The battery life is that of a gadget - not a phone.  You can get a few days without having to charge it.  In my occupation, timing is everything and having a watch die in the middle of a shift is a disaster.  I could not use it at work for that reason.  Finally, to add insult to injury, the watch stopped taking a charge after about 3 weeks of use.  This is where the real problems started.Pebble customer service is about as bad as any you could possibly imagine.  There seems to be a mandatory 2-week holding period before they will respond to any email for support.  When they respond, it is usually with unhelpful responses that do not resolve the problem, then requiring an additional 2-week delay for the next unhelpful response.  They finally concluded that my cable must be bad, after requiring me to jump through hoops like sending them photos of the phone and such.  After a few more 2-week waits the new cable arrives - surprise!  Still does not work.  Now another 2-week wait, probably more requests for documentation, pictures, etc...  I'm done with pebble and I am requesting a refund, that I'll have to wait at least another month or so for I would guess, if I even get one at all.This watch was never ready to go on sale.  Pebble does not seem to have the desire or capacity to deal with the problems.  Wait for a better offering from Samsung or Apple.

reviewText: The watch is exactly what I needed. I first saw Traser watches at a watch store, but came to Amazon for pricing. Thanks to the titanium, it's very lightweight. The dial is excellent during the day, white numbers on a black face. Reminds me of precision gauges used in sports cars in the 1950s and 1960s. At night? Incredible. The glowing needles are the reason to buy this watch. Many high-end watches look great during the day, but you can hardly read them at night. Traser should include a couple of extra links for the bracelet, though the existing bracelet fits well. Because of the nighttime clarity, this is now my favorite watch.

reviewText: I first got these NUFOOT Mary Janes at our local Menards store - a mega homeowners store like Lowe's. They were $9.99. In my older age, I must wear compression hose 24/7 and was happy to find a soft shoe to protect the expensive hose around the house. I also took them on a cruise and they were perfect to wear in the room, on the balcony as well as to the pool. With wearing them constantly and washing and drying them in the machine at least once a week, they tend to wear out quickly (2 months), but the convenience is worth it! The tops stayed perfect but the soles got holes. My Menards store no longer carries them, and I was sorry I had to pay more online.
summary: Perfect shoe to wear over compression hose

No matter where you are - in your home, in the office, in the gym, in the library, on an airplane or cruise ship, Nufoot is the perfect companion for your feet.

title: KAVU Sidewinder Bag
description: KAVU is designed for men and women with busy lifestyles. All of the gear and apparel is crafted for the adventures that leave you exhilarated, exhausted and fully alive. Whether your KAVU day involves kayaking, hiking, climbing, or just some quality time in the big outdoors, we've got you covered. It's all about attitude, doing what you love and pushing boundaries.  Founded on the now-classic Strapcap, KAVU has expanded into a wide range of men's and women's clothing, bags, sunglasses, and accessories. The products perfectly blend function and fashion, so you can rough it up all day, then wash out the trail grit and wear it to your favorite watering hole that night – and look good doing it.

reviewText: If you want boots for your kids with actual hiking-boot like traction look no further.  Most kid rubber boots have wimpy treads made for walking on wet pavement only.  I needed boots with an aggressive tread for hiking on muddy trails and these fit the bill.  There are very few youth boots with this feature on the market which is surprising.Believe it or not these boots smell like strawberry shampoo!  You may not think so, but this is actually an awesome feature.  Every other pair of rubber boots we own smell horrible when they were new.  They needed to be kept outside for a couple months to de-gas of whatever.  They must have added a sent to these to prevent that.My daughter loves them, though she wishes they were a little taller so she could go into deeper muck.  (She would like them in pink too).

reviewText: I bought it thid past Christmas for an 8 year old boy. He loves it. His mom says she does not let him wear it every day because he plays with it too much but, he still has it and in tact.That is my only piece of advice, know who you're buying it for. This child is fairly mild mannered and takes care of his things but, the curiosity of taking it apart will have him w/missing links.My son on the other hand is careless and rough, so he is already missing the links from his...but the watch face itself is still in tact.It is also nice for them when they're learning to tell time. The numbers are visible, minute markers, and has the quarter minutes. Over all, I like the watch. I didn't quite think Happy Meal when I saw it but it is toyish, it's legos.

The white hour and minute hands and Arabic numeral hour indexes make it fun to tell time. You can customize the watchband with interchangeable links or change out the blue bezel for the black one. Plus, the watch comes with an R2D2 mini-figure. The LEGO Kids' Star Wars R2D2 Watch is powered by Japanese quartz movement and features a scratch-resistant mineral crystal so not only does it look cool, it's reliable and durable. It's also water resistant to 165 feet (50 meters).

reviewText: I went snorkeling for the very first time this summer and was lucky enough to visit the Australian barrier reef.  Before I went, my parent's got me this snorkeling watch as a good luck gift.  I liked the way it looked, at first, but when snorkeling time came I actually found out that it had a lot more going for it than looks and luck.  This watch was one of the only watches in the snorkeling group that could synchronize accurately with the dive leader, which meant that I got first dibs when it came to photo ops and reef viewings.  Lucky me!
title: Pyle Sports Snorkeling Master Watch
description: With this snorkeling watch from Pyle Sports, you’ll always be ready to handle the elements. The special dive-ready design provides water resistance up to 10 atmospheres — that’s 330 feet. The PSNKW30 reports your depth up to a resolution of 0.1 ft and is equipped with a dive alarm that activates when emerging faster than 6m per minute. The watch is also equipped with a thermometer to measure the temperature of the water to 1 degree Celsius or Fahrenheit. Best of all, all this data is stored in the dive log, which holds up to 100 records, including your time and date, dive duration, maximum dive depth, min. water temperature, and dive site indication. Electro-luminescent backlight means you’ll always know the time, day or night. Color: black.

reviewText: These look slightly cheap, but with this type of material, it is impossible not to.  Other than that, this is a perfect watch for someone who is constantly washing their hands and lower arms (like a nurse).  It truly is water resistant and durable.  Plus the military time is listed for those who have trouble configuring it for notes.  For nursing students, the second hand is easy to see and you will be able to get an accurate count of respirations and manual pulses.  It's perfect for my job as a med-surg nurse and I don't think I could ask for a better watch!

reviewText: Got these for riding between 40-60F. I've ridden with them for this entire range, and they've been excellent - warm enough at 40, and breathable enough at 60 that I have no issues with sweating or overheating.I really wasn't sure when I got them whether I should go for some fancy, high technology fabric or this surprisingly simple one-size-fits-all wool warmer, but I remembered my old DeFeet arm warmers that were good in all conditions and figured I'd give them a try. My past experience with fleece-lined spandex warmers is they could get really sweaty inside, but again I have not issues at all with these.They are a bit longer than I expected (down to mid calf or more) but it hasn't been a problem. I have no problem fitting them over my quads, but I see how someone with "big" quads might (mine are pretty average). No issues with them slipping down either when biking.My only complaint is they don't "look" cool...they are reminiscent (to me) of fuzzy warm slippers, not hard-as-nails race attire due to the woolen knit. But whatever :)
title: Defeet Merino Wool Kneeker
description: The DeFeet Wool Kneeker adds the wet-weather warmth of pure merino to their already-crucial cycling knee sleeve. Serious cyclists know: warm knees mean longer rides and fewer injuries, and the one-size-fits-all Wool Kneeker keeps your knobblies toasty without the hassle of full-on tights. DeFeet recommends wearing a pair of Kneekers on any cold or wet ridebut honestly, we were doing that alreadyand you should too. Sold as a pair.Product FeaturesMaterial: 80% Merino wool, 19% Nylon, 1% LycraRecommended Use: Road cyclingManufacturer Warranty: 1 YearCountry of Origin: China

reviewText: This watch was great while it lasted, but be warned, the bezel will fall off and SURPRISE it turns out that this is not covered under the warranty. Designed in Finland, but made in China and it shows and it is clear to me exactly why it is not covered under the warranty.I should have known better from the start since 30M water resistance on something that is being marketed as 'military' is a joke. Military in this instance just refers to the black coloring/cosmetics and only serves to support the fashion aspect of it as some kind of mil-spec piece of equipment, which I can assure you it is not. I have dive watches, so this wouldn't have been used in the water that way and so I purchased it anyway......much to my dismay.The watch was decent while it lasted, it just didn't last that long. So much for Suunto 'sports' watches. Their image as a maker of high quality outdoor gear type stuff is all just a marketing ploy and has no real basis in their products or their support for their products. They are just big fashion accessories for people that want to look outdoorsy.I snowboard, mountain bike, dive, windsurf, trek, surf, climb, camp and pretty much do everything you can do outdoors and so when it came time to get a new watch, a Suunto was an obvious option. At $350 the X-Lander Military seemed it would be a ruggedly built watch and be able to stand up to that kind of use pretty well. Wrong.The first thing that went after about 4 mos. was the loop part of the watch band that holds down the extra strap portion when it is on your wrist, so that it was always sticking up. Rather than buying a new band, I just started using my girlfriend's black hairband/rubber bands for that and it worked better than the original part. The band that comes with this watch is just cheap plastic, plan on getting a different one if you buy the watch. I wish I had just returned the watch at that point.I typically only used the watch when doing stuff outdoors b/c it is too bulky for regular daily wear, so I imagine it was used maybe 50-60 days in a little under 2 years. One day, while not doing anything too taxing (driving actually), the face bezel just falls off. I snap it back on and was thankful that it didn't come off and get lost. The next time it came off, it did get lost.No problem, I assume that Suunto would have an adequate warranty and being used to dealing with companies like North Face, Patagonia and REI all the time, I assumed they would stand by their product. Wrong again. Suunto is NOT like that.I called Suunto and was informed that the warranty DOES NOT COVER the face bezel falling off. Huh? The customer service rep informs me that these are connected when they leave the factory and therefore not covered b/c they are not supposed to come off (I responded with 'that much we can agree on, they should not come off). He then goes on to tell me that it will be at least $90 to send it to them to fix it, because they have to also replace the inner metal casing part of the face. Again, huh? $90 for what would be about $7 (if that, they make the damn things after all) in parts and perhaps 30 minutes of labor? Are you kidding me?I bought a Tag Heuer Kirium watch back in 1999 and I took that everywhere and did EVERYTHING with it for years, including diving and that included a 2 year stint backpacking throughout South America and all manner of outdoor adventures and that thing has never skipped a beat. Ever. And it isn't even a sports watch AND I still wear it constantly for regular use.I told Suunto customer service person there is no way I'm going to waste $90 fixing what turns out to be just a BIG WATCH fashion accessory when they can't even guarantee me the bezel won't just fall off again and will just leave it in the gear bag as a semi-functioning backup.They won't post my review on their website for obvious reasons, so that should tell you a lot about how much they care about their customers right there.
summary: Initially a great watch, until it fell apart that is
title: Suunto X-Lander Wrist-Top Computer Watch with Altimeter, Barometer, Compass, and Chronograph
description: The ultimate option for the outdoor enthusiast, the silver Suunto X-Lander wrist-top computer offers an accurate altimeter, a complete barometer, a precise electronic compass, and a multifunction sports watch in a single elegant package. Regardless of your excursion--whether it's climbing mountains, riding a muddy bike track, or skiing off piste--you need accurate, real-time information about your surroundings to pull off a successful trip. The X-Lander contributes by not only providing important data, but also keeping track of your activities so you can make rational decisions at key moments. In addition, the watch is user-friendly and solidly built, with a non-allergenic aluminum casing, a carbon-fiber back, a durable mineral crystal glass, and a water-resistant fabric strap.The built-in altimeter, which boasts a range of up to 29,500 feet, puts all 14 of the world's 8,000-plus-meter summits within the avid climber's range. Among the altimeter's functions are an altitude measurement function that lets you follow the vertical progress between stages, an automatic 24-hour memory that stores the altitude and ascent/decent rate for every hour, and an adjustable altitude alarm. Climbers will also dig the logbook function, which lets you record total and cumulative vertical ascents and descents as well as the number of runs skied.The X-Lander also displays the current barometric pressure and temperature--a must for activities in which weather plays a factor. The device automatically records barometric data for the previous four days, with the first six hours manifested in one-hour intervals and the rest in six-hour intervals. When the reference altitude is set correctly, the instrument also displays the present sea level pressure, which makes it easier to read and understand the barometric pressure at high altitudes.And few things are more important when exploring unfamiliar territory than a compass. The X-Lander's electronic compass contributes by guiding you with cardinal or half- cardinal points and a North-South arrow. The compass can also be set to track a certain bearing, which helps you follow a chosen direction. Meanwhile, the unit's declination adjustment function allows you to correct the difference between true North and magnetic North.In addition to the variety of outdoor functions, the X-Lander also displays normal time, with such add-ons as three daily alarms, a calendar programmed to the year 2089, a stopwatch with split-time measurement, and a countdown timer. Other features include a durable negative LCD display, a user-replaceable battery, and water-resistance to 100 feet. The X-Lander is backed by a two-year warranty on parts and labor.What's in the Box?X-Lander wrist-top computer, battery, user's manual.

title: Timex Mid-Size T5K288 Ironman Sleek 150-Lap TapScreen Watch
description: Whether you're pushing yourself towards a qualifying time or a new personal best, the Timex Ironman Sleek 150-lap sports watch allows you to access information without breaking your stride. The cutting-edge performance watch includes everything a sports watch needs, including an oversized display, a huge lap memory feature, a training log, and a Target Time Pacer. As a result, you'll have an edge when training for your next sprint, distance run, or triathlon. The mid-size watch's primary distinguishing feature is its TapScreen technology, which helps you keep your eyes on the trail while you run or cycle. When TapScreen is active, a simple tap anywhere on the watch face will activate the lap timers, so you don't have to fiddle with a bunch of buttons to get to the proper screen. In a sport in which every second counts, the TapScreen function is a vital tool. The watch also includes a convenient Indiglo night mode, which makes early-morning and late-night training even easier. By holding down the Indigo button for three seconds, the watch face will automatically illuminate each time you press any button.Athletes who want to monitor their workout progress can turn to the watch's Lap Management System, which stores multiple workouts by date. The system keeps records of every lap/split and target time, along with records for your best lap and average lap speed. It also automatically stores workouts from the chronograph, letting you recall, for example, 150 one-lap workouts, one 150-lap workout, or anything in between. Perhaps the most important feature, however, is the Target Time Pacer. This feature helps you maintain your desired pace in a workout or race, so you can achieve your overall time goal. With every lap or distance segment, the watch provides audible and visual alerts to indicate whether your pace per lap is too slow, too fast, or on target. Without even a glance at your watch, you'll hear whether you're on track to meet your goal. As a bonus, the Lap Management System also recalls workout information from the Target Time Pacer, showing how much faster or slower you ran each lap and calculating your total workout time.Other features include a 24-hour countdown timer; three interval programs, each with up to 16 interval timers with user-selectable interval labels; three alarms, with daily, weekday, weekend, and day-of-week setting options; an easy-to-read display with three lines of text; open vents in the strap to minimize skin contact and increase breathability; and hydration and nutrition alarms, which remind you to refuel at regular intervals to top up essential reserves.SpecificationsChronograph: 100 hours, with lap and split timesMemory recall: 150 lapsOn-the-fly lap or split recall: YesLap counter: 199 lapsCountdown timer: 24 hours, with stop and repeatInterval timers: 16, with repeatAutomatic interval repetition counter: YesAlarms: 3 daily, weekly, weekday, or weekendTime zones: 2Case: ResinStrap: Co-molded resinWater-resistance: 100 meters

reviewText: I admit I ordered this because it's been in the news. (If you don't understand, google "Casio terrorism"). Now that I have it, I am surprisingly pleased with it as a watch, rather than as an ironic accessory.I like watches, but hate paying a lot for them. The problem is that inexpensive ones usually aren't very comfortable to wear, don't look that good, don't last, and have difficult controls. Every one of these things is not true for this Casio. Right out of the box, it was appealing. The resin strap isn't cheap looking, the watch itself is thin and light. Very readable face. I didn't even have to read the instructions to understand how to use all the controls. It's understated but retro enough to be cool in a geeky way.I can't swear to it's durability since I've had it only for a day.  I'll update this after I've used it for a while.
summary: Easy controls, thin and comfortable, geeky/cool

reviewText: I love Icebreaker. It is not the first Tech Top I got from them, and there is nothing better for a casual chilly day or for sport activities.The delivery was fast, and my Icebreaker was nicely packed.
title: Icebreaker Women's Tech Bodyfit 260 Top
description: The warm and breathable Icebreaker Women's Bodyfit260 Mid-weight Tech Top is an ideal base layer for frigid temperatures. Composed of 100 percent New Zealand merino wool, the Icebreaker Bodyfit260 line takes high-tech, high-performance sport clothing back to nature with its natural fiber construction. A base layer in cold conditions, and a standalone during high aerobic activities and in warmer temperatures, the Bodyfit 260 Mid-weight Tech Top is highly breathable, will not hold odors, and offers maximum warmth with great temperature regulation for high-performance comfort.Icebreaker uses the best superfine merino in the world, from the mountains of New Zealand. In contrast to synthetics, the Icebreaker merino fabric is finer, softer, more insulating, and more breathable than alternative fabric types. The lightweight, odor-resistant, and soft-against-the-skin fabric breathes better than other garments because each individual merino fiber breathes as well as the fabric, allowing your body to release moisture vapor so that you never feel clammy.The Bodyfit260 Mid-weight Tech Top has a three-way collar that will zip up to a high neck, zip down for cooling, or roll over. A slim fit offers a form-flattering look and flat seams provide zero-abrasion comfort. The all-natural merino fabric features a circular knit that offers a natural stretch that will maintain its shape over years of use. With a dropped tail and thumb loops the shirt will stay in place even through the most rigorous activities. Easy to care for, the Mid-weight Tech Top is machine washable and fast drying. Additionally, the Bodyfit260 fabric will not absorb odors as synthetic fabrics do.Specifications:Base layer100 percent New Zealand merino wool260g/m2 ColdCircular knit with natural stretchRaglan long sleevesHigh neckThree-way collar (zip up, down, or up and rolled)Thumb loopsDropped tailFlat seamsBreathableOdor freeSize Specifications:X-Small: Bust 33 inches; height 62.5 inchesSmall: Bust 35 inches; height 64 inchesMedium: Bust 37 inches; height 66 inchesLarge: Bust 39 inches; height 67.5 inchesX-Large: Bust 40.5 inches; height 69 inchesCare Specifications:Icebreaker garments almost look after themselves because they don't hold moisture or odor. In fact, the known record for wearing an Icebreaker non-stop is 196 days in extreme conditions. Here are a few tips to get the best out of your Icebreaker.Use warm or cool machine-wash on normal cycleWash separately first (after 2 to 3 days use) to remove any loose fibersWash with like colorsWash on a normal cycle with other hard fabrics to remove fluffingNever use a fabric softenerDo not use detergents with bleachDo not tumble dry--dry flat in the shade or on the clotheslineAbout Icebreaker Merino WoolIcebreaker uses the best superfine merino in the world, from the mountains of New Zealand in all of its garments. Icebreaker's merino fiber was created by nature to protect animals in the harsh environment of New Zealand's Southern Alps. If the fiber didn't work, the animals wouldn't survive. Recognizing that it couldn't design a better fiber, Icebreaker turned nature's merino wool into a clothing system for humans. In contrast to synthetics, Icebreaker merino is 100 percent natural. The fabric created is finer, softer, more insulating, and more breathable than alternative fabric types.Icebreaker merino forms a buffer zone around your body, keeping you at an ideal temperature in all climates and conditions. It's also lightweight, odor-resistant and soft against the skin--all qualities that will help you to perform at your peak. Because Icebreaker merino fibers are so fine, they are naturally more breathable, so you stay cool in the hottest conditions. It feels very different than synthetics, where breathability is limited.Icebreaker garments breath better than other garments because each individual merino fiber breathes as well as the fabric allowing your body to release moisture vapor so that you never feel clammy. In a warm, high aerobic environment, sweat is pulled from the body into the fabric, and dispersed and metabolized as moisture vapor through the outside of the garment, cooling the body through evaporation. In cold temperatures, when moisture is absorbed from the cold air, Icebreaker merino fibers liberate heat through a molecular process call "heat of sorption" to keep you warm.Manufacturer Warranty1-year warranty

reviewText: After seeing that many people were complaining about a horrible smell, I wasn't sure whether or not to buy this product but I finally got one at Walgreen's and I have to say, I love it!! When I got home and opened the box, I waited for the foul smell to come out but it never did. There wasn't the tiniest bit of odor on the fabric. The pockets are reasonably sized and nearly all of my stuff fit into them perfectly. Also, some people were complaining about their cellphones not being able to fit. I have an iPhone (which are pretty wide, plus it has a case) and it fit in the pockets perfectly as well. The only thing that was hard to put in a pocket was a water bottle, but once I finally did put it in there, I was able to take it out and put it back in without any trouble. I don't know how often I'll be putting a water bottle in there, so I'm not too worried. Overall, it's a great product! But my advice: buy it at a STORE instead of ordering it since apparently the strong smell comes with the online product.

title: Safety Cat Women's Self Defense Keychain - Teal
description:
IMPORTANT: When Flying Pack in Check-in Luggage Only!
The Safety Cat is a self defense, personal protection tool designed mainly for women. As women we are told for safety reasons to have our keys in our hands as we go to and from our cars. Many of us even hold our keys between our fingers walking through parking lots or out doing errands so we will be able to fight off an attacker. Unfortunately, that can be cumbersome and awkward. If you're in the position of fighting off an attacker the keys may shift in your hand making it difficult for the fight to continue. The Safety Cat self defense keychain will eliminate this problem. When holding the Safety Cat, your two fingers will be placed in the eyes of the cat and the face of the cat will rest securely in the palm of your hand. The smooth, sleek design of the Safety Cat will feel very comfortable in your hand and you will be able to grasp it firmly. Remember, the Safety Cat is used for self defense purposes only, but if you're fighting for your life the unique design of the Safety Cat is made for striking at the eyes of your attacker or attacking any fleshy part of the body.

reviewText: I have owned two Timex Ironman Watches with HR Monitor in the past.  Decided to go with a Polar brand watch for a change (11/2013) and was very, very disappointed with its lack of functionality and extremely clumsy interface.  Discarded after one week of use and decided to go back to Timex, but this time with the T5K736.  Even though the T5K736 lacks some of the sophistication of its bigger cousin, the watch does the job and has worked flawlessly to date --- I have no complaints.  I use it for marathon training, so the features I am interested in are these:  HR, avg HR for the workout, time-in-zone, lap splits (with avg HR per split), and total caloric burn.  I love the sensor system with the soft chest strap and snap on/off transmitter.  The single biggest difference between the Ironman watch and the T5K736 is that the former can remember up to three workouts, whereas the T5K736 only keeps track of the one just completed, so if you forget to record your workout --- before starting another --- your biometrics are lost.I would definitely --- without hesitation --- buy this watch again and recommend it to anyone who is interested in simple heart rate training.

reviewText: I have had the Pebble for about a month now.  I will preface my review by saying that I have been wearing a wrist watch since I bought a smartphone.  I need more immediate  gratifications than I get from pulling my phone out of my pocket to check the time.  Now I don't have to touch my phone to see the time, decline a phone call, view a text/Email, check my calendar appointments or control my music.  There is even an app for turn by turn directions now for iOS. And more apps every month that increase the functionality.With the right equipment you can control your garage door, lights, thermostat and virtually anything else you can think of, right from your wrist.The battery is good for a few days which is fine with me.  There are minor reliability issues which can easily be fixed by closing and reopening the Pebble app. I have not had the problems that many report, but I only want Gmail notifications and I get them most of the time unless the app or bluetooth has timed out which doesn't happen a lot.  Overall I love it. This is the first version of the watch and it is not perfect (yet).  However, there is so much potential with apps, games and watch faces.  If you are interested in the smart watch concept I recommend it. The watch retails for $150 at a few stores and on getpebble.com. I don't know why it is listed for more here.  (Iphone5, iOS7.0.3, latest Pebble OS.)
