reviewText: I purchased this wallet because I wanted a wallet for travel that had two compartments for bills to keep different currencies straight.  After I used it for the first time, I never went back and now use the wallet full time.  I used to go through two well-made, expensive leather wallets a year.  I have now had this wallet for nine months and it looks absolutely brand new.  The two compartments in the bill-fold are wonderful and allow me to keep bills separate when I travel and to store coupons or other stuff (like a spare key) when I'm not.  The height of the wallet is spectacular for storing Euros which stick out of many wallets.  I really like the clear window on the outside of the wallet.  I keep my ID there for use at bars or anywhere else my ID gets checked.The only drawback is that it is what it is; you're not going to look like a high-roller with a nylon and velcro wallet.  I removed the velcro to keep from drawing attention to myself when I open the wallet but it still looks like the wallet I owned when I was eight years old.Ultimately, this is one of the most practical things I own and if you're looking for a really simple wallet that is durable and well-made, buy this now.

reviewText: I got this a few years ago with the hopes to log my miles. I am a college runner at the D1 level, so I log lots of miles. I purchased this in high school, where we would run 5-6 miles a day. This watch, after some frustration getting it synced, would stay on for only 2-3 miles, then turn off. When the battery dies, you lose any data that was logged. If you run 1 mile or less in perfect weather, buy it. If you run a more than 3-4 miles, in varying weather (i.e. extreme cold, extreme hot), avoid this like the plague and go buy yourself another pair of trainers or a nice pair of spikes instead. Don't expect to use this watch everyday running 9+ miles runs like I am now. My alternative-- use a stopwatch and take splits at places on loops where the mile splits are. Much easier than this piece of junk. Way for Nike to have such a short warranty. I will never buy anything other than shoes or apparel from them again.

reviewText: Ok, here's my criteria for a perfect sun hat:Must be cheap. I'm not paying big money for this. It's a hat, it doesn't have to be pricey.Must be washable. This is something that will get dirty, guaranteed.Must be one size fits all. Why? Because the standard sizes (Small, Med, Large, Extra Large, etc) just don't fit me well. Medium is too small, large is too big.Must be packable and crushable.So, that's why this hat is perfect! What you don't see in the pics is how well it's made. The brim is thick, rigid and plenty big enough at 2 3/4 inches, the material is of good quality, the stitching and strap looks like it will hold up well.

Timing features include a 100-hour chronograph with lap or split options, 99-lap counter, 24-hour countdown timer, and second time zone with date. It uses less battery power than most other watch illumination systems, enabling your watch battery to last longer. The Night Mode feature allows you to illuminate the Indiglo night-light for 3 seconds with any button press, regardless of the mode or function.

reviewText: Unfortunately, I am not liking my second pair of Hokas as much as my fist pair. Although both 13's this second pair creases in an uncomfortable way at the toe. title: Hoka One One Men's M Rapa Nui 2 Running Shoe
description: While there are numerous "bests" in trail running, one of the worsts is when your feet get tired before your body. When you give each foot the Men's Rapa Nui 2 Trail Running Shoe from Hoka One One, you'll be bounding along the trail long after your running club has gone home, showered, and started in on their second evening cocktail. This funny-looking footwear is a dream to run on--with 1. 5 times the EVA volume that average running shoes have, every footfall is sweeter than the last. Made from air mesh, the upper lets fresh air tickle your tootsies without letting your foot flop around inside the shoe. From the tips of your little piggies to the very end of your heel, Hoka's proprietary midsole, HIR IMEVA, absorbs the shock of impact so all you feel is a sweet, soft cushion while trail-tromping. The 5mm heel-toe drop isn't minimal but isn't an elevated experience, either. The Balanced Stage Meta-Rocker Geometry keeps your foot rolling in the right direction without wasting energy on wiggles or wobbles or something in between. The bottom sports Full Ground Contact Design, which is as it sounds. The full length of your foot, plus a bit on the sides, stays in touch with the earth. Your gait isn't shaky and any kinks get a bit of correction. High-abrasion rubber is molded into dirt-gnawing 4mm multi-directional lugs. This robust sole endures the test of time without letting you slip and slide over uncertain terrain. Even if you have a chunk of concrete to cover before you hit the dusty (or muddy) trail, the Rapa Nui 2 is the shoe for you.

reviewText: I have just ordered my third watch like this.  They last about 2 years, and my second one isn't dead yet, but the top right corner display is starting to disintegrate and I don't want to be without one.  I am not complaining about the two year lifespan because I wear it ALL the time. In the shower, windsurfing, swimming, etc.  I take some pretty good falls while windsurfing and everything keeps working.  Yes, most of the silver has come off around the face and the face has lots of small scratches on it but the band is fine, the three alarms are great, the chrono is terrific.  In short, I love the features and the style, yes I wish it could take the beating I give it a little longer, but I didn't pay that much for it.That being said, I am sticking with the black band even though I like the other colors.  Lighter colors get grungy.  Also, I agree with the person who said they would like to just have the plain gray resin around the face.Also, I love that Amazon tells me when I last bought the watch, when I go to order a new one.  Thanks, Amazon!

reviewText: A well engineered and durable time piece. The X-Lander lived up to its expectation. I bought this watch new in July 2001 and proceeded to take it on 3 month expedition to Chile. During this time it got dropped down the side of a mountain, trodden on, baked, frozen and accidently dived down to 40 meters and it came through with only a few minor scratches. Compass and Altimeter very accurate. Excellent tool for trekking in the Laguna San Rafael National Park. My only critisism is the Barometer that makes weather prediction a bit awkward and it's size. It's a bit big to fit under gloves/jacket sleeves. Anyway, a very useful tool. B.T.W: Wesley Fine... How does it measure altitude in a pressurized aircraft???!!!
title: Suunto X-Lander Wrist-Top Computer Watch with Altimeter, Barometer, Compass, and Chronograph
description: The ultimate option for the outdoor enthusiast, the silver Suunto X-Lander wrist-top computer offers an accurate altimeter, a complete barometer, a precise electronic compass, and a multifunction sports watch in a single elegant package. Regardless of your excursion--whether it's climbing mountains, riding a muddy bike track, or skiing off piste--you need accurate, real-time information about your surroundings to pull off a successful trip. The X-Lander contributes by not only providing important data, but also keeping track of your activities so you can make rational decisions at key moments. In addition, the watch is user-friendly and solidly built, with a non-allergenic aluminum casing, a carbon-fiber back, a durable mineral crystal glass, and a water-resistant fabric strap.The built-in altimeter, which boasts a range of up to 29,500 feet, puts all 14 of the world's 8,000-plus-meter summits within the avid climber's range. Among the altimeter's functions are an altitude measurement function that lets you follow the vertical progress between stages, an automatic 24-hour memory that stores the altitude and ascent/decent rate for every hour, and an adjustable altitude alarm. Climbers will also dig the logbook function, which lets you record total and cumulative vertical ascents and descents as well as the number of runs skied.The X-Lander also displays the current barometric pressure and temperature--a must for activities in which weather plays a factor. The device automatically records barometric data for the previous four days, with the first six hours manifested in one-hour intervals and the rest in six-hour intervals. When the reference altitude is set correctly, the instrument also displays the present sea level pressure, which makes it easier to read and understand the barometric pressure at high altitudes.And few things are more important when exploring unfamiliar territory than a compass. The X-Lander's electronic compass contributes by guiding you with cardinal or half- cardinal points and a North-South arrow. The compass can also be set to track a certain bearing, which helps you follow a chosen direction. Meanwhile, the unit's declination adjustment function allows you to correct the difference between true North and magnetic North.In addition to the variety of outdoor functions, the X-Lander also displays normal time, with such add-ons as three daily alarms, a calendar programmed to the year 2089, a stopwatch with split-time measurement, and a countdown timer. Other features include a durable negative LCD display, a user-replaceable battery, and water-resistance to 100 feet. The X-Lander is backed by a two-year warranty on parts and labor.What's in the Box?X-Lander wrist-top computer, battery, user's manual.

title: Stick-on suede soles for high-heeled shoes, with industrial-strength adhesive backing. Resole old dance shoes or convert your favorite heels to perfect dance shoes. Colors: black, tan, or red.
description: This product is designed to be attached to ladies' shoes with high heels. You can use it to turn your favorite pair of high heels into dance shoes or to replace the worn-out suede soles of your existing dance shoes.Stick-on suede soles from Soles2dance provide ideal friction properties for dancing on well-maintained and clean wood dance floors. This innovative and unique product differs from conventional do-it-yourself add-on suede patches in that Soles2dance soles come with industrial-strength adhesive backing. You only have to peel off the protective foil from the backing and stick the soles onto your existing shoes . Other add-on suede sole products without adhesive backing require you to glue the soles on -- a messy and tricky procedure. You also have to buy that glue and learn how to apply it properly. None of that is necessary with our stick-on soles with industrial-strength adhesive backing.Will these soles stay on?After extensive testing and after having sold more than 1000 units of this and similar stick-on suede sole products with the same adhesive, we know with certainty that the adhesive stays on when used on shoes with hard leather or suede soles. On the vast majority of rubber or plastic-soled shoes the adhesive also stays on, but there are some very rare rubber or plastic compounds (notably a synthetic, rubber-like plastic material called EVA), to which the adhesive sticks less well. Fewer than 1% of our customers reported such problems. In the unlikely case that this product does not stick well to your shoes, please contact us. We respond promptly and will provide you with a satisfactory solution. Guaranteed! Chances of detachment increase when you use rubber-soled shoes with aggressive profiles that present only a small surface area for the adhesive to touch.

title: Reflexology Sandals Black & Pearl - large
description: According to the theory of reflexology, the body is divided into ten longitudinal zones, with five on each side of the vertical line. Parts of the body and organs lie in these zones.It is believed by all reflexologists that the sole of the foot mirrors the body, with the left foot reflecting the left side of the body and the right foot the right side. Hence, it is deduced that pressing the sole in the opposite place will cause an advantageous effect to be felt in the respective part of the body.As mentioned, a perceptive area in the foot indicates a problem in the consequent organ in the body. Pressing on the appropriate trouble-spot can be an effective way of relieving pain and helping to restore the body's natural balance. It can also reduce stress, improve circulation, accelerate metabolism and revitalize energy levels.By wearing the sandals you can effectively resuscitate your organs and keep them healthy, not to mention augmenting the circulation in the feet and legs, easing exhaustion and helping to alleviate the uneasiness of tired, aching feetIn order to stimulate these reflex points in your feet, reflexology shoes and sandals have been introduced. Reflexology Sandals were created so that people can be capable of giving themselves this type of therapy effortlessly and inexpensively.This is achieved with the massage nodules on these sandals. They are raised to follow the contour of the feet. The pegs basically stimulate the reflex area when one wears the sandals and  are removable, so that you may customize the sandals to target specific pressure points.A number of people begin by wearing these shoes for only five minutes in the beginning and then progressively increase the periods, for example while doing the dishes or while talking on the phone. Make sure that you do not wear these sandals all day long as they are only meant to be worn for short periods of time to stimulate your reflexology points.

reviewText: These Sloggers are the best looking  & most comfortable plastic clogs I've had in the past 12 years. reviewText: I've gone back and added to the following review:  In theory, this is a great watch with a great concept:  It's sleek, it's face is changeable, and it's supposed to sync with your smartphone's bluetooth so you can receive texts, emails and see who is calling you.  However, the software is completely dodgy and unreliable.  After a couple of days, emails were no longer showing up on the watch.  A few days later, texts disappeared.  Then, the charger blew up (my computer actually ejected it with an error message that said the USB device was using too much power).  After days of no longer being able to charge my watch, it simply died.  I tried to recharge it with someone else's charger but it was too late.  It's dead Jim.  And so apparently is Pebble's customer service which has ignored all of my attempts to contact them.  These guys are obviously in over their heads, being completely unprepared for the demand for their "amazing" new product that clearly was not ready for prime time.  Save your money and wait for the iWatch.Update:  I finally heard from customer service (so they do exist).  They are overnighting a charger to me via Fed Ex.  Also, after trying to charge the phone again with my friend's charger, I pushed all of the buttons randomly and finally my phone came back.  Oh, and now I'm getting emails, texts and phone calls.So, I've added a couple of stars (although I'm still mad that customer service is so not on top of things) and I've decided the watch isn't a total dud.  However, it's still not really worth the expense and I'm sure the future smartphone watches from Apple, Android, etc. will be much better.  Overall, my experience has been disappointing.

reviewText: I've had my Victorinox Swiss Army Renegade watch since 1999 or 2000. Mine originally had a nylon strap, but it is essentially the same watch. it's been great over the years and I still include it in my watch rotation. Other than a single band replacement, and some new batteries, it has been a flawless, trusty companion. The design is timeless, and it's not a hefty as some newer watches, but that's part of its charm. The case is a tough back plastic; mine has developed some "personality" over the years, yet still looks great. This is a great choice if you're looking for an affordable Swiss-made timepiece.
title: Renegade Watch
description: The Victorinox Renegade Watch Made in Switzerland with a precision Swiss analog quartz movement.

reviewText: I really like this watch, but battery ruins all the fun. 18 hours is about the most I can get out of it. If you're the kind of person who really depend on PDA, then do yourself a favor a buy a proper PDA device.

Other features include convenient drop-down menus, alarm reminder window for recurring appointments, a memo pad, and a selection of different time and date displays to give your Wrist PDA its own personalized 'dial' when not in PDA mode. reviewText: I was looking for something to replace a Timex Triathlon HRM without spending an arm and a leg. I knew that I wanted a continuous monitor which means a strap. Even though I work out regularly, I am not necessarily interested in the ability of keeping multiple workouts stored. If you want a simple HRM that is easy to use, then this is the one. It is the third Timex HRM that I have owned and I've had good luck with all three. It just works. Some reviews indicate problems with the strap picking up the signals correctly. This is probably more a function of an individual's body chemistry, etc. as I have never had issues with this. There are some conductive gels that can help with this if it is a problem. Bottom line is that you would be hard pressed to find something of equivalent value in this price range.

reviewText: Bought this (16 GB) for my new build, an ASUS P8Z77-V Deluxe Intel Ivy Bridge i7-3700. Yes, these memory sticks are listed on the QVL; specifically approved by ASUS for this mobo. After a week I started getting random BSOD's showing "memory management error". After tinkering for a while with everything -very aggravating-, I pulled out 2 sticks (Bank 0) and BSOD's went away, put them back and BSOD came back. Conclusion: POS memory. Confirmed with Memtest86+, 2 bad sticks. Never again will I buy Corsair memory. Ended up getting Kingstons HyperX's, a bit more expensive but no problems at all and they do have lifetime warranty unlike Corsair (wonder why?) Once more: YOU GET WHAT YOU PAY FOR!

title: Suunto X-Lander Wrist-Top Computer Watch with Altimeter, Barometer, Compass, and Chronograph
description: The ultimate option for the outdoor enthusiast, the silver Suunto X-Lander wrist-top computer offers an accurate altimeter, a complete barometer, a precise electronic compass, and a multifunction sports watch in a single elegant package. Regardless of your excursion--whether it's climbing mountains, riding a muddy bike track, or skiing off piste--you need accurate, real-time information about your surroundings to pull off a successful trip. The X-Lander contributes by not only providing important data, but also keeping track of your activities so you can make rational decisions at key moments. In addition, the watch is user-friendly and solidly built, with a non-allergenic aluminum casing, a carbon-fiber back, a durable mineral crystal glass, and a water-resistant fabric strap.The built-in altimeter, which boasts a range of up to 29,500 feet, puts all 14 of the world's 8,000-plus-meter summits within the avid climber's range. Among the altimeter's functions are an altitude measurement function that lets you follow the vertical progress between stages, an automatic 24-hour memory that stores the altitude and ascent/decent rate for every hour, and an adjustable altitude alarm. Climbers will also dig the logbook function, which lets you record total and cumulative vertical ascents and descents as well as the number of runs skied.The X-Lander also displays the current barometric pressure and temperature--a must for activities in which weather plays a factor. The device automatically records barometric data for the previous four days, with the first six hours manifested in one-hour intervals and the rest in six-hour intervals. When the reference altitude is set correctly, the instrument also displays the present sea level pressure, which makes it easier to read and understand the barometric pressure at high altitudes.And few things are more important when exploring unfamiliar territory than a compass. The X-Lander's electronic compass contributes by guiding you with cardinal or half- cardinal points and a North-South arrow. The compass can also be set to track a certain bearing, which helps you follow a chosen direction. Meanwhile, the unit's declination adjustment function allows you to correct the difference between true North and magnetic North.In addition to the variety of outdoor functions, the X-Lander also displays normal time, with such add-ons as three daily alarms, a calendar programmed to the year 2089, a stopwatch with split-time measurement, and a countdown timer. Other features include a durable negative LCD display, a user-replaceable battery, and water-resistance to 100 feet. The X-Lander is backed by a two-year warranty on parts and labor.What's in the Box?X-Lander wrist-top computer, battery, user's manual.

reviewText: "Casio Men's PAG40-3COS Pathfinder Triple Sensor Watch"The Swiss Army tool of watches. Every watch should have the features this watch has. Even with a large 50 mm case this is a light weight watch. It is so light weight, I barely know it's on my wrist. All the sensors have their own large dedicated buttons. I find the barometer/thermometer feature very convenient. I never have to wonder or check the weather, I always know what temperature it is at the simple push of a button. And it can predict what the weather will be! The other feature that, I also find convenient to have is the compass. At the simple touch of a button you know which direction your going. This watch at first may make some seem a little timid. A few minutes with the instruction booklet (if you need it) and you will have all your sensors calibrated or to your liking. I prefer Fahrenheit when it comes to temperature settings and not Celsius. This watch will come with the Celsius setting from the factory. I haven't been hiking with it but the altimeter is nice to have so you can track your altitude, cumulative ascent and decent in route to your destination.  A feature that some may not consider is the clasp. The clasp is a fold over clasp and secures quite nicely. No worries of it coming lose and losing the watch. The mineral crystal is very thought, I have owned it for weeks now and not a single blemish. This is a watch that you can where to work or play. The watch is more than just watch it's like a computer on your wrist. Finally, and maybe the ultimate feature is that it's solar powered. Never have to worry about battery's again! Amazon.com has the best price on the internet. There may be an unfamiliar website that may have it for a few dollars less but it's not worth the risk. For the piece of mind and price you can't go wrong. If you have any second thoughts about this watch remember this an easy watch to use and has an easy to read instruction booklet. The booklet is a bit thick but most of the information you will not need. The box that it comes in appears to a be "green" box (recycled or Eco-friendly). Which, I find very appeasing that it's environmentally friendly. The Casio engineers did an awesome job on this watch. If you want to be in the know. You will want this watch. I would highly recommend this watch to all military service members.Note: I have received many questions about getting an accurate temperature reading. You will have to take off the watch and let sit to read the ambient temperature for several minutes to get a precise temperature.
summary: "Casio Men's PAG240T-7CR Pathfinder Triple Sensor Watch"

reviewText: I am not one to buy "cheesy" gifts, and I actually wasn't even certain this gift would be good for my girlfriend. She is working on her Master's in Psychology, so, when I stumbled upon these, I had a big chuckle. I don't know why, they just caught me as hilarious. So, I bought them on the spot.I figured it'd garner a slight smile, or a chuckle, but when she opened these things, everyone had a HUGE positive response. I had no idea that the red tongues were actually cloth around the wearer's toes, so her wigling her toes made Freud flap his tongue. The perfect gift, and I hadn't given it enough credit!My girlfriend says they "slip" as she walks due to them being so soft and fuzzy, but that they're extremely comfortable.Also of note: Freud's eyes are a little cross-eyed looking in the real life slippers. Not a problem, and adds to the sort of "Muppets", silly feel of the product.

reviewText: This is an interesting watch.Notes:- Love the two sandwiched layers on the dial. The white background underneath the cut-out dial is totally lumed, so nice effect with the glow coming through the digits (I believe that Momentum uses Superluminova). There is a very slight space gap between the two layers, which results in a very subtle shadow on the white layer when viewed under light. Nice.- Propeller second hand is also different. It ticks every second, in case you're wondering.- Really like the offset crown, like the Seikos.- Kind of wish it had a date. Not a big deal.- Size of hour/minute hands feels nicely proportionate to the dial size. This is a problem with some watches.- This is a solid, chunky watch; may be too big for small wrists. The size is somewhat offset by the fact that it's a pretty plain (i.e., non-busy) dial.- I purchased elsewhere with the heavy rubber diving band. Doesn't seem to be available here.

reviewText: This is just a FYI to anyone thinking of buying this watch.  I did, for a number of reason, one of which is I liked the large white numbers on the black face of the watch.  Well, when I received the watch, the numbers were not exactly white.  The picture above, and others of this model, clearly show white numbers, but the watch I received had goldish, shiny, metallic numbers.  I emailed the seller, Kenmar Watches (sold through Amazon), and asked about it.  First they said they didn't know what I was talking about, and then they emailed me saying yes, the numbers were a shiny, metallic gold color.  And that was all this model of watch had.  I returned the watch.  Just a FYI for anyone thinking of buying this watch.  The pictures are misleading.

reviewText: This is the first FiveTen shoe I have owned.  Before I purchased this shoe, I had climbed in the Evolv Geshidos the La Sportiva Testarossas.  Obviously those shoes do very different jobs, but I'll compare them based on size.  My street shoe size is an 11 US.  My Geshidos, which are the most similar to the Anasazi of any of my other shoes, are a size 11 US.  The Geshidos fit my foot great length wise but were slightly wide making side edges a little more tenuous.  My Testarossas are a size 42.5 EU; I definitely should have gotten these smaller as they stretched to be slightly too long and are too wide for me to get good side edging.With that info in mind, the 9.5 Anasazi fit's my foot (after two and a half weeks of climbing at least 3 times a week) great so far.  It is a somewhat aggressive fit as my toes knuckle more than in any of my other shoes.  The width, however, is great so far.  I can edge better in these shoes than in any pair I have yet owned.  The heal box is very pronounced which fits my heal perfect.  I've been able to make good heal hooks on tenuous holds in them without any slippage.  The lack of downturn makes these shoes less than ideal for really steep climbing, but that's not what I bought them for.  I bought them as all-around shoes, and so far I think they're doing perfectly.They are great for face climbing on small edges.  If aggressively sized, they are decent for roofs.  They are flat enough to comfortably drop your heel for slab climbing.  This may be my go-to all-arounder from now on.  This isn't an all-day, multi-pitch shoe in this aggressive size, though.
summary: Great fit for a slender foot

reviewText: I was apprehensive about buying the SportBand after reading all the negative reviews, but in the end I went for it, figuring that the potential benefits of having a really useful and relatively inexpensive instrument outweighed the inconvenience of returning it should it prove to be a lemon or a dud. I've only had this for a day so I can't speak about its durability or longevity, but since I went through my own period of frustration in getting the watch to work, I thought I might share a few tips and save someone else a lot of hair pulling. After combing the interwebs to troubleshoot this thing, it's actually proven to be an amazing little device. What I really fault Nike for is not including and displaying this info in a conspicuous manner - say, in the instruction booklet or in the online FAQ, where people might actually see it and use it to solve the issue, rather than dreading the inevitable call to an ignoramus in customer service that will end up boosting your blood pressure and heart rate in all the wrong ways.So anyways, if your watch won't link up to the sensor here's what you can try:1. Wake up or restart the sensor. I understand many if not most of these units will be shipped with the sensor in sleep/standby mode. Push on the button once with a pen until it clicks to wake it up. To reset, hold the button for 3 seconds until it goes to sleep. Then push on the button again to wake it up.2. Reset the watch. Push and hold both the top & side buttons for 10 seconds until the screen reads "Nike." You'll have to plug it into your computer and use the Nike+ software to re-input your settings for weight, time, etc.3. Push and hold the SIDE button for 5 seconds. That makes the watch find the nearest sensor and link to it.I had to do all these things to resuscitate my SportBand which I thought was DOA but was in fact just a little groggy from prolonged hibernation. The other problem people - and by people I mean myself included - seem to be having is that the calibration is waaaay off. I went for a 1-mile run at a track to test its accuracy and the watch said 0.3 miles, and wouldn't even let me set the calibration in the software - WTF!? Well, turns out Nike has an expanded user manual in a PDF buried in their site somewhere, from which I culled this useful tidbit:1. THE SENSOR NEEDS TO BE ORIENTED WITH THE LOGO SIDE UP, SWOOSH POINTING TOWARDS THE HEEL. This seemed to do the trick, with the accuracy jumping from an execrable 30% to a whopping 90% - and it finally even let me fine-tune the calibration! Since I use a pouch that threads through the laces and wraps around a few times, this actually took some careful visualization.2. Apparently the sensor should be oriented as flat as possible on the shoe. I changed the location of my pouch from up by the tongue where it was nearly vertical, to down near the toe where it's more horizontal.3. This is probably just voodoo, but it may help the wireless transmission to have the sensor on the same side as the hand you're wearing the watch on. Left wrist, left shoe, and vice versa.Hope all this helps!

reviewText: One would think that a watch that is supposed to be water resistant to 100 meters would be able to be rinsed off while washing your hands.  This is not an isolated incident because I had the same exact watch with the same problem.  I only thought it was my bad with the first watch for not aligning the rubber seal on the back cover when changing the battery.  I love the design and look of this watch.  The mode and selection are very intuitive.  The band is not hard plastic (this was an important requirement for me). It is an attractive watch.  I don't even need to check the back to see if it is made in China.  I'm sure of it.  Can anything of good quality come out of China?  How can the label say water resistant to 100 meters? The good news is that the warranty is 1 year.  I wonder how much effort it will take to get it replaced though.  I'll probably get a customer support agent in India.  I'll probably take the replacement.  I don't know why I keep going back.  Perhaps I should look for a Timex Anonymous meeting!

title: Croakies XL Eyewear Retainer
description: The original Neoprene Eyewear Retainer -- patented in 1978 -- remains one of Croakies' most popular models. Made of snug-fitting, grippy neoprene material, its ends tightly grip your frames, so while you may lose yourself in your favorite activity, your glasses will remain securely strapped to your head.DetailsMade of durable HyPUR-cel neopreneColorfast and washableTwo inches of adjustmentFits most framesMade in the USAAbout CroakiesIn 1977, a local ski patrolman from Jackson Hole Mountain Resort in Wyoming came up with an idea for an eyewear retainer that would grip his shades through all kinds of alpine adventures. Using an old wetsuit and some sharp scissors, he made the first pair of eyewear retainers. The ingenious device was based on the design of a Chinese finger trap, and quickly became a hit with local ski patrolers. Demand picked up quickly for the patrolman's invention, which was initially nameless. Back in the seventies, the Jackson Hole ski patrol used the nickname "croakies" when they couldn't think of a word (think "thing- amajig"), but it finally stuck on the world'd first neoprene eyewear retainer.Croakies headquarters are still in Jackson Hole, with production in Bozeman, Montana. The inspiration remains the same -- to create eyewear retainers and accessories that provide comfort, style, durability, and functionality to active people of all ages. Croakies products are sold by retailers throughout the United States and in over 30 countries around the world. They've even been used out of this world, having become standard issue on the Space Shuttle in 1990.

reviewText: I just wanted a basic, understated, durable watch and thought this would fill the bill. It has. It's beautiful in a minimalist sort of way, with fluorescent numbers and hands, and a whisper quiet mechanism. Setting the time and date is simple and it keeps perfect time. The cover of the watch casing and the wrist band appear to be made of the same tough, black rubber, and enough holes are punched in the band to keep my wrist from sweating.One aesthetic note: The face of the watch looks more elegant than the photos here. I think they either removed the crystal to reduce reflections in the photo or used a polarizing filter. Be advised that the clearly visible inner ring encircling the numbers in the photo is actually a 45-degree-ish beveled surface that completely disappears when the crystal is in place.

reviewText: As the title says, it is a decent watch for a nurse. A nurse washes his/her hands multiple times a shift and a wrist-watch is a potential fomite. Having a watch clipped to your shirt is easier and it prevents transmission of germs.One downfall of the watch is that if you have to wear an isolation gown, the watch is under the gown.The glow in the dark face is pretty bright at night.It gets three stars because the chain was put on backwards - the face of the watch would only hang facing me instead of away from me - one cannot see the watch if the face of the watch is against your body. I had to perform minor surgery. I had to take pliers (which I padded with several layers of electrical tape to prevent scratching the watch) and I had to pry apart the first link (the biggest one) - where it attaches to the pin (there is an opening under the part where it attaches to the pin that you cannot see, but it is there). I then reversed the pin and squeezed the link back together. Now the watch hangs with the face away from me.I had some issues when the pin bent and the watch fell off of me a couple of times until I was able to bend the pin back to the spot so it did not fall off anymore. Unfortunately one of the times it fell off, the face cracked - but it still worked fine.I got this as a gift Christmas of 2007. The battery just died yesterday - so it lasted two years.I will probably just get a new battery for it. The crack is not bad at all.

reviewText: This watch is a classic. It won't ever go out of style for one reason, it does what it's supposed to and it does it well. Nothing more, nothing less.Easy - It's digital so you look down and you know what time it is. Seems silly but being able to quickly read the time is nice.  Programming it is a cinch. There are only three buttons so even if the buttons weren't labeled (which they are) it's not hard to figure out. There are only basic functions like alarm, time, date, and stopwatch. That's it. You don't have to go through a million different options and weird combinations of button presses.Durable - I wore it on a camping trip to Zion and Bryce Canyon. It survived rocks, dust, water, mud, sun, and my recklessness. There's hardly a scratch on it and the watch face is still immaculate.Comfortable - It's very light and compact. I can wear it all day and not notice it. My wrists are on the smaller side so the size of the watch face suits me well. It's not overbearing like a lot of other watches for men. By the way, this is fine as a unisex watch. Much respect to all people who wear this watch, men or women. You get extra points in my book.Reliable - The battery will last. Time-telling is pretty accurate. Oddly durable. Simple. You won't mind wearing it. Also, really cheap. There's a reason these watches haven't changed. You'll have the peace of mind of knowing you can lose it and abuse it, and easily and inexpensively replace it. No need to baby it or worry about it.It seems odd to buy a watch when everyone uses cellphones for everything but once you start wearing a watch you really are more observant of time. It truly does keep you cognizant. This item belongs in the category of things like Nokia phones, Koss Porta-pros, IBM mechanical keyboards, and old Swingline staplers. They just simply work. Form and function going hand in hand. So you could spend money on a restaurant burger, a bottle of wine, a movie ticket, a drink at a bar or... you could buy this watch which will last you the next 20 years. You could also keep browsing trying to find the perfect watch but think of all the time you might be wasting.If you want to scream the word "practical" then this timeless timepiece is for you.

reviewText: I used to buy the polarized fishing glasses at Wally World.  I still would, except that in a small town the selection and availability are very limited, and they won't special order for you.  So, with the help of the reviews here (thank you), I decided to try these.  At $14.40 ea (with free shipping) I ordered four pair.I wear sunglasses whenever I'm outside.  I buy a lot of cheap sunglasses rather than one pair of expensive ones (it hurts when you break them, lose them or scratch the lenses).  Doing this review made me realize what a huge inconsistency in product there is where I used to buy cheap sunglasses.  I always tried to buy the same/similar style, but now I don't think they were even mnfg'd by the same company.  They come in the same package, but it's like a jobber buys whatever is around and packages them with his label.  I've had glasses that were OK and others that variously hurt my ears, pressed into the sides of my head, dug into my nose, pushed off my face, flew off my face (not doing athletics), slipped down my face, and sat cockeyed.  I've had rubber pads pop out, glued on pads slip around and fall off, and glasses without rubber pads.  A few had the frame color painted on - the paint pealed off leaving me walking around with paint chips on my face.  And, of course, some with lenses that pop out.I've had these for about a month and have not experienced any problems so far.  The lenses are narrower (in height) than I like, but they do the job.  The tinting is good, polarization works well and they claim to block 100% UV A&B.;  A snug, comfortable fit and rubber pads on the temples and nose piece keep them secure.  The temples bow around my head (no pinching) and curve in at the ears.  The plastic is pliable enough to hold well but not be uncomfortable.  They are pretty light and at first I thought flimsy, but they are stable, tight, and don't twist and bend.  Hopefully they last a few more months, until the lenses are too scratched up to see out of.  What more could I want from cheap sunglasses (except some scratch resistance)?. . . P.S. I've started adding the price to my reviews.  I find it quite useful to see price history.Update 10/06/12 Still on my first pair!  These glasses have lasted much longer than I thought they would.  The lenses are not yet all scratched up, they're still tight in the frame and the frame is still tight.

reviewText: I'm a casual jogger/runner: 5-20mi a week. I'm also a tech nerd, so I thought seeing my run data would help motivate me to run more often. This is the first run tracking device I've owned.The sportband itself is ok though possibly a little overpriced. You have to download and install a small software utility to allow the sportband to sync with the Nike website. I had some difficulty getting the software to work correctly the first 2-3 times I synced a run. Now it seems to be working ok. I simply plug the usb portion of the band into my laptop and it syncs: no problem.The Nike+ website is a little disappointing. I was hoping for more reporting features other than just length of run. I'd like to compare runs to other runs in graph form and put custom tags on runs based on the route I chose that day. The visualization of data is pretty week for anything other than total length/time of your run. Who knows, maybe Nike will improve the website in the future.The site will also post your runs to FB if that's your thing.Based on comments I've seen on various sites, there are probably cheaper, better, and more accurate solutions out there for tracking your run stats. That said, this is probably a decent starter solution for a casual runner like myself.
title: Nike+ SportBand (Black/Cool Grey/Silver) (Discontinued by Manufacturer)

reviewText: This robe looks nice online and had a good heft to it taking it out of the package.  However, the directions say that washing before wearing the robe will help it last longer.  So, I washed it and dried it, trying to ignore the shed pieces all over the washer.  And, like previous review stated, when I pulled it out of the dryer there were holes where the seams came apart.  I want to like this product, but when I have to sew the thing back together just to be able to wear it for the first time and worry about how it will hold up to future washing or even just wearing it, that totally supersedes any desire to like it.  My advice, despite other reviews to the contrary, keep looking!

title: Safety Cat Women's Self Defense Keychain - Teal
description:
IMPORTANT: When Flying Pack in Check-in Luggage Only!
The Safety Cat is a self defense, personal protection tool designed mainly for women. As women we are told for safety reasons to have our keys in our hands as we go to and from our cars. Many of us even hold our keys between our fingers walking through parking lots or out doing errands so we will be able to fight off an attacker. Unfortunately, that can be cumbersome and awkward. If you're in the position of fighting off an attacker the keys may shift in your hand making it difficult for the fight to continue. The Safety Cat self defense keychain will eliminate this problem. When holding the Safety Cat, your two fingers will be placed in the eyes of the cat and the face of the cat will rest securely in the palm of your hand. The smooth, sleek design of the Safety Cat will feel very comfortable in your hand and you will be able to grasp it firmly. Remember, the Safety Cat is used for self defense purposes only, but if you're fighting for your life the unique design of the Safety Cat is made for striking at the eyes of your attacker or attacking any fleshy part of the body.

reviewText: The bottoms of these covers will not hold up on the pedals.  If you use cleats they will do a lot better since your foot is not moving around on the pedal.  However, you will have to cut a hole for the cleat in each of them.  In one ride under 4 hours, I had the bottoms torn up.  Like the Tech Exec. says these covers are fine for occasional or emergency use and they do compact down to fit in a small pouch.Showers Pass does make another cover that is supposed to have a much stronger bottom.  They call that boot their " Touring Shoe Cover".  I just ordered a pair since they were on closeout for $35 rather than $70. They're available at showerspass.com under Closeouts.These might work great if you're trying to protect your Allen Edmonds shoes from getting wet between your car and your office front door.  Just make sure your car is within 100 feet of your office or these will be shot in a week.

reviewText: This watch is a fine collectible and a great bargain. Delivered before the due date and in a nice case with the "G" symbol imprint. title: 1920 Triangular Masonic Pocket Watch Freemason Lodge Replica
description: This fine reproduction timepiece is a tribute to a rare 1920's era Swiss-made pocket watch designed to honor the Freemasons. This triangular pocket watch measures 2.4" x 1.9" x .38" and features alloy steel construction with an antique silver finish. The outer case is adorned with the unbroken chain of Brotherly Love and Affection symbol of the Freemasons. The face of the watch replaces the standard Roman numeral hour marks with symbols and imagery unique to the Rites of Freemasonry. This truly distinctive timepiece includes a coordinating gift box. To replace battery pull on the notch located on the back of the watch at the top of the triangle then the back will open where the battery is located. Sigma Impex, P-252.

title: Casio PRW 3000 Watch
description: The Casio PRW 3000 Watch won't cook your dinner, carry your gear, or give you a foot rub after a long hike, but it'll do just about everything else you can imagine on your next trek, backpacking trip, sailing mission, or time-traveling adventure. This little aluminum, resin, and mineral glass case packs a mind-boggling array of tech tools, from an altimeter to a barometer to a compass to a thermometer, all run by a solar-powered battery that'll last for up to seven months on a single charge. The altimeter, which measures in precise one-meter increments, has automatic and manual logging functions and can hold up to 30 records of high/low altitudes, cumulative ascent and descent, with a range from -2,300 to over 32,000 feet. That's just the beginning. The PRW 3000 has a barometer as well, which has an automatic pressure-change indicator to alert you to sudden swings, along with a pressure tendency graph and pressure differential graphic to give you a longer-term idea of what the weather's doing. To keep you on course, the compass has a graphic 16-point display for one-glance orientation, a bearing memory to keep you on route, and declination adjustment so your bearing is accurate no matter where in the world you are. We haven't even mentioned the one thing the PRW 3000's designed to do first and foremost--tell the time. It receives six atomic signals a day to ensure you're always on time, has 12- and 24-hour displays and five alarms so you never miss a mealtime, and sunset/sunrise, time zone, and calendar data. There isn't even space to discuss the stopwatch, 100m waterproofing, automatic LED, power-save function, or battery-life indicator, but trust that they're there.

reviewText: I have had a pair of the Heavy Worker pants for several years, and bought a new pair because mine are starting to look ratty. They haven't worn out, and will probably be around for a long time to come. I have loved them, and will continue to wear them when I don't have to look presentable for clients.The new ones, however, have a radically different cut. The waist/rise is at least and inch higher, and the legs are longer with the kneepads lower for the same listed size. They also feel wider and generally less tailored. reviewText: I purchased these gaiters for both trail running and hiking. They are made from decent materials, and are put together well. However, getting them to fit properly is difficult which is why I gave it a low rating. This gaiter relies on a friction strap to pull itself into place over the collar of your shoe. There are no grommets or hooks to latch on to your laces to prevent ride-up. If you don't honk down on the straps, the elastic in the bottom cuff will pull away from your trail shoe letting debris in. Boots (like the ones depicted) have less of an issue, but still require a lot of tightening. The whole strap-tightening-thing is very frustrating. It's difficult to do when I'm in my nice warm house. I wonder how frustrated I'll feel out on the trail.

reviewText: My husband got these via Kickstarter, where we were promised the sun, moon, and stars.  We use Apple and while we understand that the watch has better functionality with Android than it does Apple, we did not get nearly what the creators promised.  If you invested in a company that did so poorly, the SEC would investigate.The only thing this watch does for me, besides tell time, is sometimes but not always show text messages and it IDs incoming calls.  My husband has better functionality because...let's just say his apple device is different than mine.Pebble does not acknowledge tweets.  If you send an error report, they reply with a canned response that doesn't address your specific problem.  They further warn you that sending more than one message about your malfunction will only delay their response.They just released a new operating system.  Pebble sent me 7 notifications in 2 days about it.  I was in Yosemite, with limited internet and phone connectivity.  Updating the watch's OS was not my priority.  One notification will suffice!  I revoked their permission to send me notifications.When I tried to update the OS after returning to the connected world, the update failed repeatedly.  My husband also had to try repeatedly but his at least happened.You have to charge this watch...great, I needed another device to charge.  This means I leave my $150 watch home frequently because it's charging.  Also when I first had the watch, I used a white watch face, which drained the battery in a couple days, not the five or six that Pebble promised.  Charging sucks a lot of power out of your ports and it is slow.  If the watch isn't fully charged it may die before you get it back on the juice.  Sometimes for me, the charge only lasted a few hours after being connected for many.  My husband had to buy a new charging port that runs off our house electricity to charge these watches.
summary: It Works Fine Only as a Watch

reviewText: The Pebble Smartwatch is an indispensable device for me.Starting with the hardware - beautiful, simple and eye catching, Pebble is lightweight and robust. The buttons have a solid click to them and the screen is wonderfully visible in bright sunlight, as advertised. I've also tested it while swimming and it seems to be watertight as advertised.Since I began using my Pebble there are a few things I never anticipated it would help me out with - namely two factor auth text messages from Google and discretely keeping up with text messages. The former is worth the value of the watch alone - two factor auth text messages are a massive pain given you have to pull out your phone, unlock it, etc. When they are directly on your wrist, they are practically frictionless. Additionally, mundane text messages that may have previously interrupted dinner or a good conversation can be quickly reviewed by peeking at my wrist.One of my biggest concerns about a smartwatch was the battery life - I'm consistently getting a week with Pebble. And quite frankly if I had to charge my watch on a daily basis, I wouldn't be interested. I'm hopeful that future updates make this even longer.It's also been great to see the progress in software updates that the Pebble folks have been putting out - they clearly want Pebble to get better over time and it shows. Excited to see the watch and the platform grow.
summary: Pebble delighted me in ways I couldn't have anticipated

While I own several very nice expensive watches already I faced an issue that I can no longer see them clearly. That is why I searched for a watch with larger easy to read face with large numbers. THIS watch passes my vision test with flying colors!!!! Even when my eyes are very blurry I can still see this watch fairly clearly!!!!!!A plus for me is that this watch will really do it all from timing my cycling laps to just being an ordinary watch for my everyday life. If I need a dress watch I'll dig out one of my older watches that I can't see as well but they will just be bling on my wrist for the occasion!ADDED 2/12/13.....................The INDIGLO light just failed which from what I read online is a common fault with this watch. This is a darn shame to since this is a fine time piece otherwise.ADDED 2/13/13.......Today the alarm started going off even tho I never set it!!  Alarm will also not shut off no matter which button I push!!!!!ADDED 2/15/13.....Sent watch back for warranty replacement. Hope I get a better one next time since this is a nice watch really.

reviewText: When I first got this I wasn't sure how it would really change how I interact with my phone. It has totally changed my experience with my iPhone. description: Eco-Organize, Now you can finally say no to single-use plastic dry-cleaning bags. It is the perfect solution for pesky plastic, annoying twist-ties and cluttering paper garment covers. 4-Bags-in-1, Here's how it works: at home your Green Garmento serves as a hanging or standard hamper, on your trip to the drycleaner it functions as a duffel bag, and at pick-up your dry-cleaned clothes will be hanging and protected inside your Green Garmento, without a single-use plastic bag in sight. The Green Garmento is 4-in-1 reusable laundry, duffel and hanging garment bag created to help eliminate the estimated three hundred million pounds of single-use dry cleaning plastic that annually clog US landfills and waterways, threatening marine and wildlife. reviewText: I am very happy with this watch as it has exactly everything that I needed. The best part is that it has auto-countdown timer that works without any hassle.  I use it mainly for daily medication (multiple dose) reminder and it works wonderfully with its built-in vibration mode.  The timer warns you twice, with a single vibe (or beep), before going off when it reaches the end time: First, at 10 minutes prior, then at 5 minutes prior and finally going off at the 0.  It resets the countdown automatically as set before right then without you having to do anything (except maybe stop the vibration/beeping with one touch before it stops automatically).  And if you wanted to reset the timer for the next reminder soon after finishing the activity you are using the timer for, it's easily done manually.It's handsome in looks. Has indigo background as the light feature. With 2nd zone clock, it's very handy when travelling without having to change the main clock.Perfect for those who need silent reminders throughout the day and have hearing impairment, or do not want to disturb others with beeps.  Works wonderfully for medicine reminders with multiple doses throughout the day.  It also has two separate alarm clocks.
summary: Great product at a great price!

reviewText: I guess I'm just too cheap to spend hundreds on a winder, after all, I just want to wind my watch, not add a piece of furniture to the room. I had passed by this item to purchase a more popular name winder last time around and ended up with a noisy, unreliable unit that died on me 2 months out of warranty. This one is a little "funky" to load and start-up until you get the hang of it, but once you are past that (actually it is so simple that I almost "over-engineered" the first time around), this winder is extremely quiet and reliable.  I use it on my Rolex at the six minute per hour setting and it works great (it also fits my Panerai).  The only complaint is that there is no cover on the unit so the watch is exposed, but the ease of use and total silence when operating make up for that minor detail.  I definitely recommend this item.

reviewText: I was all set to buy a G shock when I thought....*What if a lower end model from the same Company would be good enough?*I think I paid $11 after shipping and the watch works great.I clean carpets and wax floors at work and am constantly bumping it and getting it a little wet.  It hasn't croaked so far.  I figure if it does I will go buy the $50 dollar G shock and if it doesn't then I saved myself $40.  Easy to follow set-up.  A Simple button on the side to switch between Military time and Standard time.  It has a nice little light to see the time when it is dark. reviewText: Icebreaker is a fabulous product. They make great ski tops for coldWeather days. Love the feature that holds your thumb so that the sleeves don't ride up.
title: Icebreaker Women's Tech Bodyfit 260 Top
description: The warm and breathable Icebreaker Women's Bodyfit260 Mid-weight Tech Top is an ideal base layer for frigid temperatures. Composed of 100 percent New Zealand merino wool, the Icebreaker Bodyfit260 line takes high-tech, high-performance sport clothing back to nature with its natural fiber construction. A base layer in cold conditions, and a standalone during high aerobic activities and in warmer temperatures, the Bodyfit 260 Mid-weight Tech Top is highly breathable, will not hold odors, and offers maximum warmth with great temperature regulation for high-performance comfort.Icebreaker uses the best superfine merino in the world, from the mountains of New Zealand. In contrast to synthetics, the Icebreaker merino fabric is finer, softer, more insulating, and more breathable than alternative fabric types. The lightweight, odor-resistant, and soft-against-the-skin fabric breathes better than other garments because each individual merino fiber breathes as well as the fabric, allowing your body to release moisture vapor so that you never feel clammy.The Bodyfit260 Mid-weight Tech Top has a three-way collar that will zip up to a high neck, zip down for cooling, or roll over. A slim fit offers a form-flattering look and flat seams provide zero-abrasion comfort. The all-natural merino fabric features a circular knit that offers a natural stretch that will maintain its shape over years of use. With a dropped tail and thumb loops the shirt will stay in place even through the most rigorous activities. Easy to care for, the Mid-weight Tech Top is machine washable and fast drying. Additionally, the Bodyfit260 fabric will not absorb odors as synthetic fabrics do.Specifications:Base layer100 percent New Zealand merino wool260g/m2 ColdCircular knit with natural stretchRaglan long sleevesHigh neckThree-way collar (zip up, down, or up and rolled)Thumb loopsDropped tailFlat seamsBreathableOdor freeSize Specifications:X-Small: Bust 33 inches; height 62.5 inchesSmall: Bust 35 inches; height 64 inchesMedium: Bust 37 inches; height 66 inchesLarge: Bust 39 inches; height 67.5 inchesX-Large: Bust 40.5 inches; height 69 inchesCare Specifications:Icebreaker garments almost look after themselves because they don't hold moisture or odor. In fact, the known record for wearing an Icebreaker non-stop is 196 days in extreme conditions. Here are a few tips to get the best out of your Icebreaker.Use warm or cool machine-wash on normal cycleWash separately first (after 2 to 3 days use) to remove any loose fibersWash with like colorsWash on a normal cycle with other hard fabrics to remove fluffingNever use a fabric softenerDo not use detergents with bleachDo not tumble dry--dry flat in the shade or on the clotheslineAbout Icebreaker Merino WoolIcebreaker uses the best superfine merino in the world, from the mountains of New Zealand in all of its garments. Icebreaker's merino fiber was created by nature to protect animals in the harsh environment of New Zealand's Southern Alps. If the fiber didn't work, the animals wouldn't survive. Recognizing that it couldn't design a better fiber, Icebreaker turned nature's merino wool into a clothing system for humans. In contrast to synthetics, Icebreaker merino is 100 percent natural. The fabric created is finer, softer, more insulating, and more breathable than alternative fabric types.Icebreaker merino forms a buffer zone around your body, keeping you at an ideal temperature in all climates and conditions. It's also lightweight, odor-resistant and soft against the skin--all qualities that will help you to perform at your peak. Because Icebreaker merino fibers are so fine, they are naturally more breathable, so you stay cool in the hottest conditions. It feels very different than synthetics, where breathability is limited.Icebreaker garments breath better than other garments because each individual merino fiber breathes as well as the fabric allowing your body to release moisture vapor so that you never feel clammy. In a warm, high aerobic environment, sweat is pulled from the body into the fabric, and dispersed and metabolized as moisture vapor through the outside of the garment, cooling the body through evaporation. In cold temperatures, when moisture is absorbed from the cold air, Icebreaker merino fibers liberate heat through a molecular process call "heat of sorption" to keep you warm.Manufacturer Warranty1-year warranty
